<LEADPARA>  EVERY actor in a long-running weekly series, sooner or later, wants a change
of pace, a chance to break away from playing the same character week after
week, an opportunity to use skills that otherwise might wither away from
disuse.;   So far, this month has been loaded with TV-series stars "breaking
away" through made-for-TV movies: Roseanne Arnold of "Roseanne" taking a
breather from the Conner household by playing a single mom in "Backfield in
Motion"; Michelle Lee of "Knots Landing" stripping off her makeup to be a
distraught mother in "My Son Johnny"; Susan Ruttan of "L.A. Law" playing a
murderous nurse in "Deadly Medicine"; Betty White of "The Golden Girls"
playing a romantic lady on a last fling in "Chance of a Lifetime"; Judith
Light of "Who's the Boss?" poisoning her husband for his insurance money in
"Wife, Mother, Murderer"; and sitcom stars Steven Weber of "Wings" and Mary
Page Keller of "Baby Talk" teaming up for an anguishing drama tonight,
"Deception: A Mother's Secret."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  TV Magazine  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DANZA WITH WOES
SERIES COMEDIAN KNOCKS 'EM DEAD AS HUNTED HOOD  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  DEAD AND ALIVE; Sunday night at 9 on  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     But nobody has broken away from his usual image with any greater success
than Tony Danza, the lovably goofy housekeeper of "Who's the Boss?" He'll stun
his fans this weekend as a small-time killer on the lam in ABC's "Dead and
Alive," tonight at 9 on Chs. 7 and 11.;   In this harsh, unsettling and
uncompromising crime docudrama, Danza isn't just getting in a little "r&amp;r"
from the series grind. What he's doing is slapping the Hollywood establishment
wide awake to his potential as a dramatic actor by delivering a powerful but
impressively contained performance that proves he's ready for a whole new kind
of star venue.;   Danza plays Gus Farace, a real-life Staten Island hood who
made the awesome mistake of killing a federal undercover drug agent during a
street transaction that went bad in 1989.;   The movie begins with that tense,
bloody sequence, then turns into a grim two-hour chase film that has the feel
of "Odd Man Out" with a heavy overlay of "GoodFellas," as Farace attempts to
elude not only an army of converging law enforcement officers but also teams
of hit men from his own mob family.;   Portrayal digs deep;   Rather than play
this low-life as a folk hero, Danza peels Farace down to his essence: a
vicious sociopath whose uncontrollable fear and pathological suspicion of
everyone finally turns him into a mad dog at bay.;   With Danza's dazzling
performance as its core, "Dead and Alive" becomes a brilliant docudrama that
sets out to expose the soul-dead heart of the current Mafia. The mobsters we
see aren't the feudal barons of the "Godfather" films or the psychopathic
pranksters of "GoodFellas," but a collection of icy pragmatists who realize
the only way to get the federal heat off their operations is to "whack" one of
their own before he makes a deal to save his skin.;   It was a brilliant
strategy worked out by Asst. U.S. Attorney Charles Rose, played by Ted Levine,
the serial killer from "The Silence of the Lambs." Rose led the search for
Farace. He reasoned that the only way to flush Farace out of hiding was to
hassle his mob brethren so badly that their moneymaking activities would be
disrupted enough to make them turn the fugitive in.;   That isn't exactly the
way it worked out, but the strategy did turn the mob against a "soldier" who
had become a liability, making Farace more and more desperate as the law drew
its dragnet closer to him, and one friend after another was either "offed" by
his former mob allies or, worse, sent to kill him in order to save their own
lives.;   This isn't a movie for the squeamish. In one sequence, mob goons
blow off a man's elbow to convince him they mean business. The bloody finale
is a stomach-churner.;   Danza's fans also may be bothered by what they see.
In his seven seasons on "Who's the Boss?", Danza has become a sex symbol to
millions of women, the handsome, good-natured hunk of many female dreams. In
"Dead and Alive," he's the stuff of nightmares. With his hair cut short and
his tattoos showing, Danza looks incredibly menacing. His hoodlum personality
is even more intimidating.;   Critics, take note;   In one sequence, Farace is
wearing a long blond wig as a disguise while hiding out in a girlfriend's
apartment in Yonkers. When a pal slips and calls him by his real name, Farace
goes psycho and heaves everybody out of the joint. There isn't a trace of the
old Tony Danza in that explosive scene.;   In another, the coldblooded Farace
warns a friend what will happen if he betrays him: "You'll never hear the
hammer click!";   In still another, the paranoid Farace sees the manhunt for
him come up on the "America's Most Wanted" TV series. Farace is convinced they
don't put stories on that show unless they already know where the fugitives
are hiding out. Panicked, he calls up the TV show from his hideout and tries
to bully the operator into admitting they're setting him up.;   Though Danza
has done a few dramatic roles, none has been in this league. His tightly
reined, credible performance ought to permanently stifle the critics who still
consider him nothing but an ex-prizefighter who lucked into a simple-minded
comedy role on a sitcom that became an enormous hit ("Taxi"), then parlayed
that into a career playing an amiable lout on "Who's the Boss?";   The Tony
Danza on display in "Dead and Alive" is an accomplished actor capable of
tapping his own roots in the streets of Brooklyn for the inspiration to
deliver a performance that blows you away like a blast from a Magnum and
resonates with the ring of truth.;   That's the best reason to watch this
intense docudrama, a worthy addition to the growing list of films about the
complex workings of America's criminal empires. (box)  </TEXT>
