<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shows Not Available for Previewing Might Hold Some Surprises</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Several new network shows weren't available for
screening in their entirety, pre-season. AP Television Writer
Kathryn Baker looked at the casts, producers and plotlines for clues
to how they might do.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Snoops</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   CBS' ``Snoops'' stars Tim and Daphne Maxwell Reid, late of
``Frank's Place'' as TV husband-and-wife in this hour comedy-drama
set in Washington, D.C. He is a noted professor of criminology at
Georgetown University. She is a protocol officer with the State
Department. Together, they solve matters of international intrigue
and just plain, old crimes. ``Snoops'' goes up against NBC's
bikini-clad ``Baywatch'' on Fridays.
 
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Island Son</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Miniseries regular Richard Chamberlain returns to series
television, once again as a doctor _ he played ``Dr. Kildare'' in
the 1960s _ in CBS' ``Island Son.'' Who wouldn't have been lured
back to the weekly grind with a show set in Hawaii? Chamberlain
plays Daniel Kulani, a doctor at a large Honolulu hospital, who was
adopted at birth by a native Hawaiian couple and has a Hawaiian
businessman brother. Little is known about the show, but one of the
co-executive producers, Nigel McKeand, wrote for ``The Waltons'' and
``Family.'' ``Island Son'' goes up against NBC's ``Midnight Caller''
and ABC's ``thirtysomething'' on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Rescue 911</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   CBS will try to match NBC's success with ``Unsolved Mysteries''
by launching its own ``reality-based'' series, ``Rescue 911,''
featuring graphic re-creations of actual emergency calls. It is too
graphic for its early time period on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Free Spirit</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The most unlikely sitcom of the new season is ABC's ``Free
Spirit,'' starring Corinne Bohrer as Winnie the Witch, housekeeper
to a stern single dad and his three young children. This one will
need a magic wand. One of the co-executive producers' credits
include ``Diff'rent Strokes'' ``Women in Prison'' and ``Facts of
Life.'' ``Free Spirit'' should be a free agent soon. It goes up
against CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote'' and NBC's ``Sister Kate'' on
Sundays.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Living Dolls</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Another ABC sitcom looks a little more promising. ``Living
Dolls,'' about four young models sharing a New York apartment, is
something of a spinoff of ``Who's the Boss?'' Tony Danza and Alyssa
Milano will make occasional guest appearances. Michael Learned
(``The Waltons'') plays a former model who serves as the girls' den
mother. ``Living Dolls'' goes in on Saturday after ``Mr. Belvedere.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The Young Riders</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Also a possibility is ABC's new Western ``The Young Riders,'' the
story of the young men who rode Pony Express. The cast is a passel
of newcomers, except for Josh Brolin. Creator-supervising producer
Ed Spielman also created the 1970s Eastern Western ``Kung Fu.''
``The Young Riders'' gets the Thursday time period opposite NBC's
comedies, but with its kid-appeal, it might last long enough to see
the sunset.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Mancuso, FBI</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   NBC is rounding out its all-new Friday lineup with two shows
derived from successful TV movies of last season. Robert Loggia
reprises his role as the rough-edged FBI agent Nick Mancuso that he
created in the political thriller ``Favorite Son.'' ``Mancuso, FBI''
looks like a good bet as a politically sophisticated crime drama
that could attract a cult following, a la ``Wiseguy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Baywatch</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Starting out Friday is ``Baywatch,'' a silly lifeguard drama that
the alarmists among us can take as more evidence that civilization,
as well as the beach, is eroding. Watch. It'll be a hit. The rerun
of last season's movie was in the top 10 in the Nielsens. David
Hasselhoff (``Knight Rider''), Parker Stevenson (``Hardy Boys''),
and former Miss Universe Shawn Weatherly (``OceanQuest'') star as
the scantily clad protagonists. Here's irony for you: This is the
only show on the schedule from ballyhooed GTG Entertainment, the new
production company established by Grant ``Quality Television''
Tinker, former chairman of NBC.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
