                       Dead and Alive
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Tony Danza is Gus Farace, the minor New York hoodlum whose
murder of an undercover narcotics agent made him the target
of a major manhunt. Both the police and the underworld wanted
Farace, the cops because of what he had done to one of their
own, the mob because the lawman's murder had brought intense
pressure down on Farace's Mafia colleagues. An interestingly
layered two hours, the film has a certain urbanity and style.
It's also a relief to see Tony Danza as something other than
the golden-hearted nitwit of the sitcoms, though every now
and then the creepy softness of his sitcom personality pops
up here, too. We get to see more of Mr. Danza's estimable
torso than is absolutely necessary, but he makes a quite
convincing Farace.
   -- 9-11 p.m. EST, on ABC.
                                                                                                       

                   Deception: A Mother's Secret
                                                                                                       

   The weight of sentimentality hangs heavy on the first part
of this film about a devoted father who tries to adopt his
dead wife's son. That, however, doesn't prevent the story
from growing on a viewer, as the husband discovers the truth
about the boy. Thanks to Steven Weber's skillful portrayal of
the father, and Robert Gorman's wrenching performance as the
boy, the film is, by the end, a tale that should wring tears
from all but the stone-hearted.
   -- 9-11 p.m. EST, on NBC.
                                                                                                       

                      Monday, Nov. 25
                    A Mother's Justice
                                                                                                       

   What's left to say about rape this TV season? The answer
is plenty, and there's always room for more, given the
network's evidently bottomless attraction to this theme. In
this fact-based movie, a mother hunts for her daughter's
rapist, a saga that may well have been more interesting in
life than it turns out here. Meredith Baxter, who never
looked grimmer, portrays the revenge-seeking mother, whose
obsession is fueled by her own memories of an unhappy first
marriage in which her husband made her feel degraded. Two
tales of male oppression are, needless to say, better than
one. The rape victim's boyfriend, an unemancipated lout, is
also on hand, enlarging the circle of oppressors to three,
but who's counting? The mother's hunt for the rapist ends
unsurprisingly. That there emerges, from all this flapdoodle,
any effective drama at all (as there does in the
mother-daughter scenes) is the real surprise.
   ---9-11 EST, on NBC.
                                                                                                       

                     Tuesday, Nov. 26
                   Breaking the Silence
                                                                                                       

   This is "L.A. Law" with psychosexual trimmings -- an epic
about a star attorney with a frightful past that features
sleaze, psychosis, incest, child molestation and sundry
similar prime-time attractions. Gregory Harrison is
effectively -- if unintentionally -- unappetizing as the
lawyer who must navigate his way through this dark world and
wide, under the weight of his aberrations. For someone with
two hours to annihilate, this could be just the thing.
   -- 9-11 EST, on CBS.
                                                                                                       

                      Sunday, Dec. 1
                     She's Been Away
                                                                                                       

   By far the best Masterpiece Theatre offering of the
season, this is also Dame Peggy Ashcroft's last and mostly
brilliant performance. A drama of an aged woman coming out
into the sun -- and also into the modern hell of noise and
ugliness -- after 60 years in a mental institution, it is a
work of surpassing power and, at least up to the end, of
subtlety. Too bad its creators saw fit to turn so delicate
and cutting a film into a kind of female buddy movie at the
finale, with Dame Peggy's character, Lil lian, tearing off
with her nephew's embittered wife on a British version of
Thelma and Louise's spree. This piece of agitprop is
particularly gross, coming as it does on top of a nuanced and
wonderfully tense hour and three quarters, in which Lillian
is reintroduced to the world by a dutiful nephew. Dame
Peggy's character is an unyieldingly hard and tough portrait,
notwithstanding numerous muddling efforts in the script to
portray insan ity as a form of romantic rebellion. James Fox
is splendid as the decent nephew, all briskness and certitude
under the thickest of skins. Geraldine James is better still
as his complicated and brooding wife.
   -- 9-11 EST, on PBS. PBS air dates and times vary so check
local listings.
</TEXT>
