<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THREE BLOCKBUSTERS SUNDAY -- ONE'S WORTH IT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Television  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  (box) WIFE, MOTHER, MURDERER; Sunday night at 9, Chs. 7, 11; (box) THE RETURN
OF ELIOT NESS; Sunday night at 9, Chs. 4, 8;   WITH the World Series out of
the way and no cataclysmic international events scheduled, the networks are
bringing out their conventional weapons this weekend for the kind of outright
warfare we've all come to expect on a Sunday night during the November ratings
sweeps.;   ABC, CBS and NBC all will unleash first-run made-for-TV movies
against each other Sunday night at 9, each starring a popular TV name with a
high recognition rating and each based, sort of, on true stories.;   The best
of the lot is CBS's "My Son Johnny," which features a devastating performance
by Michele Lee of CBS's "Knots Landing" as the mother of a modern Cain and
Abel. The show also has dynamite turns by Rick Schroder and Corin Nemec as the
sons who hate each other.;   If you have a tough time picking a favorite, let
me help out: This is one of the best movies of the TV season. You won't get
acting any better all year long.;   Far less interesting, because it's about a
person you won't be able to stand, is ABC's "Wife, Mother, Murderer," the true
story of Marie Hilley, who blithely poisoned her husband and her daughter,
eluded police for years, faked her death, then posed as her twin sister so
convincingly that she duped her own husband.;   Though you'll be fascinated by
the offbeat performance of Judith Light of "Who's the Boss?" as murderous
Marie, you may need to bathe a few times after seeing this film.;   Finally,
there's Robert Stack of NBC's hit "Unsolved Mysteries" series, reprising the
role that made him a TV star several decades ago, in "The Return of Eliot
Ness," which tells how the aging Ness came out of retirement in 1947 to avenge
the murder of a former colleague by the gangsters who took over Al Capone's
Chicago crime empire.;   This movie isn't as bad as it sounds, but it
stretches credibility the way Charles Durning stretches his belt loops. (Since
Durning is in the movie, you can see for yourself.) If you still have a soft
spot in your heart for Stack's old "The Untouchables" series, this may be hard
to resist.;   For me, though, the irresistible one is "My Son Johnny," the
heartbreaking story of a tough, almost psychotic older brother (Schroder) who
has constantly beaten up on his younger brother (Nemec) since childhood, with
the tacit approval of his old-fashioned mom (Lee), who believes it's natural
for brothers to scrap, and it makes men out of them.;   Ultimately, though,
the mother is forced to face her own guilt when one of her sons winds up dead
and the other on trial for murder.;   Lee plays her role sans makeup and with
an ethnic dialect. It's an incredible turn for her after so many years in
"Knots Landing" and so few opportunities to show her other dimensions as an
actress.;   She's backed up by two of TV's best young actors. Schroder, the
former child star of movies such as "The Champ" and TV's "Silver Spoons"
sitcom, is now a mature 21 and has developed into a superb dramatic actor.
This vengeful, violent, sadistic role will stun his fans.;   It also may bowl
over fans of Corin Nemec, who know him only from his Fox sitcom, "Parker Lewis
Can't Lose," to see him vanish completely into the persona of the tormented,
moody Anthony. It's his best work since he starred in the miniseries "I Know
My First Name is Steven.";   Fine acting also is the main attraction of "Wife,
Mother, Murderer," in which the generally sunshiny and attractive Judith Light
plays a tawdry and amoral woman we finally believe is capable of any evil.;  
After watching Light with David Ogden Stiers in a gross bathtub scene, her
fans may stop longing for her to finally get it on with Tony Danza in "Who's
the Boss?" Frankly, I found her performance a hoot and quite clearly the only
reason to watch this otherwise sick-spirited film.;   Finally, there's "The
Return of Eliot Ness," which isn't likely to satisfy the craving so many of us
had for a sequel to Brian DePalma's big-screen version of "The Untouchables."
Robert Stack isn't Kevin Costner, nor is the stunt man who doubles for him in
so many scenes.;   In this fanciful tale, Ness teams up with the son (Jack
Coleman) of his murdered pal to track down the killers. He needs to because
the son is a cop, and Ness is a retiree. At first, the son is reluctant
because he has swallowed the mob-planted story that his dad was on the take.; 
 "He wasn't on the take, son," growls Ness. "He was untouchable!";   Actually,
it's kind of fun to see the 1947 hoods' reaction to Ness when he introduces
himself around town. Naturally, most of them thought he was either dead or
hosting a reality crime show somewhere. They're not used to meeting legendary
lawmen in the flesh.;   Ness also shoots up a good deal of Chicago, badge or
no badge. This time the bad guys use bazookas as well as tommy guns, but
they're still no match for the deadeye dick with the deadpan stare. When he
survives a well-orchestrated hit in a hotel lobby, he seems too lucky to be
true.;   But when he tells gang moll Lisa Hartman that "easy eyes and easy
women don't work on me," you know he's still as trustworthy as he was before
they sent him to that nursing home or wherever the heck he's been for the past
30 years.  </TEXT>
