<LEADPARA>  FOR those who get so bored with network television that they stop watching the
new season by December, there may seem to be even more new shows than
advertised this fall.;   That's because each of the networks has given fall
berths to a number of "early starters," shows introduced in the last few
months of the past TV season that did well enough to earn commitments for a
full season.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  TV Magazine  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SECOND CHANCES FOR TRYOUT SHOWS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Fall Preview / Early Shows  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Here are the shows that made the grade last spring:;   "Blossom" (NBC),
starring Mayim Bialik as a teen TV star trying to grow up normal.;   "Northern
Exposure" (CBS), a whimsical drama about a young urban doctor who's now
practicing medicine in a remote Alaskan community. It actually began in the
summer of 1990 but turned hot when it got a second tryout last spring.;  
"Dinosaurs" (ABC), a sitcom starring "animatronic" puppets, which takes place
in prehistoric times, when dinosaurs lived in housing tracts.;   "American
Detective" (ABC), a "reality" show in which the cases of real-life police
detectives are recounted with mostly real sequences videotaped as they
happened.;   "Expose" (NBC), a tabloid-style news show that goes after major
stories.;   "Baby Talk" (ABC), a sitcom about a baby who "thinks" in the voice
of Tony Danza. Originally on the 1990 fall schedule, it was delayed until
mid-season due to a last-minute cast change.;   "Sisters" (NBC), a one-hour
comedy/drama about the relationships of four sisters. (box)  </TEXT>
