<DESCRIPT>  ENTERTAINMENT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  TONY Danza has closed a long-term, multifaceted deal with Columbia Pictures
that will be announced next week.;   His Katie Face Productions, Danza says,
will develop and produce movies (one in the works is autobiographical), TV
programs, a children's television show -- and a reality series that's
particularly close to his heart. He says of the latter: "It's a show that will
offer assistance to inner-city kids and chronicle their progress."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DANZA DEAL INCLUDES MOVIES, SERIES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Grapevine  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Danza, who's just starting what he says will be his final season of "Who's
the Boss?" says that ABC has already expressed interest in the reality show he
terms, "The only thing that really excites me right now.";   FROM THE INSIDE
LOOKING OUT: While Goldie Hawn is busy making "House Sitter" with Steve
Martin, her production partner Anthea Sylbert is busy putting together the
next project for their company. It's called "Mrs. Faust," it's to be made for
Disney, and it will have Hawn playing a woman who almost sells her soul to the
devil. Hawn wraps "House Sitter" in November, and might squeeze in a
big-screen acting assignment before "Faust," says Sylbert. She also says their
long-planned "Babe West" project is not making any progress, that studios
"can't seem to deal with Vietnam." "Babe West" would have Goldie playing an
entertainer who goes to Vietnam to perform for the troops, "rather an amoral
story -- but a great one," says Sylbert. "Someday we'll get it made. I vow!"; 
 INDUSTRY EYE: Director Arthur Hiller plans to take a much needed break when
he finishes post-production on John Goodman's "The Babe." Because of Goodman's
series commitment to "Roseanne," says Hiller, "we had only limited time with
him, so I've been working around the clock." Hiller segued directly to "Babe"
shooting from the feature film "Married To It," which debuts Sept. 27. After
"Married To It," he wanted a break, but says that when he read the script for
"The Babe," "I just couldn't say no.";   PERSON TO PERSON: Gena Rowlands is
keeping busy. Just a few months after she completed the CBS TV movie "Face of
a Stranger" with Tyne Daly in Seattle, she's returned to that region to
co-star with Holly Hunter in TNT's three-generation family drama "Crazy in
Love." When "Crazy" is completed next month, she'll return to the business of
distributing the five features of her late husband, John Cassavetes, that she
owns ("Shadows," "Faces," "Woman Under the Influence," "Killing of a Chinese
Bookie" and "Opening Night"). Rowlands reports that undertaking is "going very
well" and now involves frequent trips to Europe.  </TEXT>
