<CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Mommy deadliest: Judith Light, plays a woman who poisons
her husband and tries to kill her daughter, played by Kellie Overbey.; PHOTO:
Judith Light plays Marie Hilley (Color)  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  TELEVISION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WIFE, MOTHER, MURDERER; Sunday night at 9, Chs. 7, 11  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'WHO'S THE BOSS' STAR TRIES NOT-SO-LIGHT ROLE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>  AFTER more than seven years of the hit comedy series "Who's the Boss?,"
viewers have come to know actress Judith Light. Now it's time to see if
they're ready for Judith Dark.;   They'll find out Sunday night, when Light
takes her most daring leap yet off the ledge of sitcom security to play an
evil, soulless real-life murderer -- a woman so radically different from the
cheerful, sophisticated and caring Angela Bower of "Who's the Boss?" that
thousands of startled viewers may call the network to find out if that was
really Light.;   The vehicle is a TV docudrama called "Wife, Mother,
Murderer," in which Light plays Marie Hilley, a diabolical Alabama woman who
poisoned her husband and daughter for insurance money and led a bizarre double
life while hiding out from suspicious authorities.;   "Lots of people want to
know why I would play a character like that, why we'd want to show that to
people," Light said in her dressing room after rehearsing with the cast of her
ABC sitcom. "But until we see it, we can't stop it.";   Light says the show is
of value because it allows viewers to see how far a charming sociopath can go
and how much damage she can do by just taking advantage of people's goodwill
and willingness to trust an attractive woman.;   More personally, though,
Light found herself fascinated by the complexity of Hilley's character and was
hungry for a really challenging part.;   "I'd never played anyone like that --
which is why it was so difficult," Light said. "I think she was a consummate
actress. I don't have to be comfortable playing someone who's not likable, but
I found out Marie was very likable in many ways. She was charming and had
slept with a lot of people in town, so she wasn't unattractive. But she used
people for her own means.";   Light studied mounds of court transcripts, read
scores of newspaper accounts and talked with two people who knew Hilley well:
her daughter, Carol, who survived her mother's attempt to kill her, and Lt.
Gary Carroll, the police officer who handled her case.;   "Carol's a pretty
incredible gal," said Light. "She doesn't like to talk about it much, but you
get the gist of things.";   A life of pretense;   As for Carroll, Light found
his stories about Hilley very useful in penetrating the woman's psyche.;  
"When he arrived at her house to question her for the first time, he found it
impeccably clean," Light said. "She had baked cookies for him and had the
Bible open on the table. This was a sociopath in every sense of the word.";  
Playacting was fundamental to Hilley's personality. In her most outlandish
escapade, she faked her own death, then pretended to be her own twin sister.
She even fooled her second husband. That gave Light yet another chance at
displaying her virtuosity, creating subtle differences between the real Marie
and her make-believe sister.;   Light got so far into the character that she
says it took her at least a month to get Hilley out of her system after
filming stopped. As souvenirs, she keeps pillows in her dressing room that
have slipcovers made from her Marie Hilley costumes, a gift from the costume
people on the picture.;   Though the script doesn't try to explain why Hilley
was the way she was, Light researched her so thoroughly that she thinks she
may have the answer.;   "I believe she grew up without discipline," she said.
"There was no one to stop her; so she pushed and pushed against society until
society became a parent and punished her by putting her in jail. Even then,
she manipulated the warden and got out on a furlough. It wasn't until her
death that she actually was stopped.";   Though she's well aware some fans may
prefer seeing her in safe romantic-comedy roles, Light is confident her large
following is willing to go along with her on her occasional adventures in Risk
City, even one as revolting as this.;   "My audience is very faithful to me,"
she said. "They know I'm an actress. They don't write letters to me that
start, 'Dear Angela.' They welcome my doing something different, so I don't
think this role will be problematic for them.";   Still, it may be hard for
viewers to see Light as quite the same loving mom on "Who's the Boss?" after
watching her feed arsenic to her only daughter on "Wife, Mother, Murderer."
And it may be tough to keep going along with her romantic but wholesomely
proper relationship with live-in housekeeper Tony Micelli (Tony Danza) on the
sitcom after seeing her bathtub scene with her overweight lover in Sunday's
movie.;   Doesn't want to be typecast;   Yet Light feels it's a chance she
must take since she wants to keep surprising people, especially the people who
decide which actors can handle which roles. Now in her eighth season with
"Who's the Boss?," she's grateful for all it has done for her career, but
doesn't want it to be all she does from here on.;   "I think I know why people
typecast you," she said. "By pigeon-holing you, they understand you better. I
have a lot of empathy for that, even if I don't like it.";   Light first ran
into typecasting when she left the daytime drama "One Life to Live," where she
won two Emmys as Karen Wolek, and came to California to seek the wider
prime-time audience.;   "They said, 'We know she can be dramatic, but can she
be funny?"' she recalled. "Then I was funny, and they said, 'But can she be
dramatic?' ";   That was a harrowing period for Light, who quickly landed a
guest role on "St. Elsewhere" and then didn't work again for eight months.;  
"I kept asking everybody, angrily, what I was doing wrong," she said. "The
truth is: I was afraid I wasn't going to make it, and I was covering up my
fear with anger.";   Her next part turned out to be the Angela role in "Who's
the Boss?," an immediate hit. It gave Light her first real chance to be both
funny and stylishly sexy for a nationwide audience. It also began eight years
of public pressure for Angela and Tony to "get together" in all senses of the
word. It finally happens this season, as they head for the altar.;   Light
broke into prime-time dramatic roles when her agent convinced ABC she could be
credible as the heartbroken but determined mother of youthful AIDS-victim Ryan
White in a 1989 TV movie. It has been easier for her to land offbeat roles
like Marie Hilley ever since.;   That may be important in the future, when
"Who's the Boss?" reaches the end of the line. Moved to a new night this fall
-- Saturdays at 8 -- the series has slipped in the ratings. Many feel it will
end this season with Angela and Tony finally settling into marriage.;   "It's
not over till the fat lady sings," Light responds. "I think this series will
have life in it even after Angela and Tony are 'doing it.' There's enough
juice left in the characters for people to want to see them after they're
married. Anyway, I'm not like those actors who say they can't wait to get out
of their series. That's like ignoring the breast that's feeding you. I like
doing other things, but I'm very grateful for what's on my plate."  </TEXT>
