<DESCRIPT>  TELEVISION; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  NEW television shows based on hit movies are supposed to be especially blessed
because most people already know what they're about and don't have to be
bludgeoned into tuning in for at least a sample look.;    Now I'll tell you
about one that not only wasn't blessed, but might even have been cursed.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'BABY TALK': IT WAS DEFINITELY TIME FOR A
CHANGE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Television  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     It's called "Baby Talk." You may have seen it around the halfway mark of
the past TV season -- and lived to regret it. Nestled among the four "TGIF"
comedies on ABC's Friday night lineup, it collected a huge pile of bad
reviews, but not many fans who couldn't face life without it.;    At first,
"Baby Talk" seemed a surefire hit. It was under the care of Ed. Weinberger,
one of TV's most successful writer-producers, whose hits date back to "The
Mary Tyler Moore Show." It also starred Connie Sellecca, a well-known TV star
from ABC's popular "Hotel" drama series. And it was based on one of 1989's
biggest hit movies, "Look Who's Talking.";    But trouble nipped at its heels
from the start.;    First, Columbia, the studio behind it, decided not to call
it "Look Who's Talking." They feared it would confuse people to have a TV
series by that name while "Look Who's Talking, Too," the movie sequel they
brought out last summer, was still playing in theaters.;    So they blew the
advantages of having a "pre-sold" title.;    Then, just before "Baby Talk" was
due to go into production, Sellecca left. It was, the network said, a mutual
decision. Nobody wanted Sellecca playing the unwed mom of a baby who "thinks"
with the voice of Tony Danza, including Sellecca.;    Without a new star to
stand in for Sellecca, Weinberger couldn't deliver the show on time, and ABC
had to remove it from the fall lineup.;    Then, when Weinberger hired former
"Newhart" star Julia Duffy to take over the role, all the scripts had to be
revised. Sellecca is tall, dark and dramatic and Duffy is short, blond and
comedic.;    Nor was it helpful that Duffy soon learned to hate her role. Once
the reviews came in and a critics' poll named it worst show of the season, she
wanted to crawl into the baby's cradle and pull its blanket over her head. She
wanted out, out, out.;    Normally, that's where my story would end. "Baby
Talk" was getting bad reviews, slightly better than mediocre ratings and was
about to lose its star for the second time. Nothing about it was working.
Everything pointed to cancellation.;    So, guess what? Come Friday, Sept. 20,
at 9:30 p.m., "Baby Talk" will have its season premiere. If we're lucky, none
of us will recognize it.;    Gone are Weinberger, Duffy and everybody else in
the cast except Paul and Ryan Jessup, the twin babies who share the role of
little Mikey. (Danza returns as the baby's voice.) The setting will shift to
an apartment building in Brooklyn Heights and the story won't stop so often to
let us "hear" Mikey's thoughts.;    Mary Page Keller, who last season played a
single mother on ABC's "Life Goes On," will take over the role of Mikey's mom,
Maggie, and Scott Baio ("Happy Days," "Joanie Loves Chachi") will play her new
boyfriend, James, a young musician/composer who lives next door.;    For all
practical purposes, it's a completely new show, but with two leads who more
closely resemble the stars of the original movie: Kirstie Alley and John
Travolta.;    That's fine with new producers Bernie Orenstein and Saul
Turteltaub ("Kate &amp; Allie," "Sanford &amp; Son"), who didn't care for the show
last season. Neither did Baio, for that matter. Keller, mercifully, never saw
it.;    So why is something called "Baby Talk" coming back? My best guess is
it avoided disaster by having a concept ABC still had faith in and so-so
ratings, mostly due to the protected time slot it had behind three consecutive
hits.;    The new producers hope to take better advantage of that same
protected time slot by concentrating more on the budding romance between
Maggie and James, less on the wisecracks from the baby's brain.;    "We found
that the characters in the last version of the show were not very realistic,"
said Turteltaub at a recent meeting with the press to discuss the show's
overhaul.;    Turteltaub and Orenstein didn't like the idea of two workmen
practically living round the clock in Maggie's house, nor her constantly
leaving her baby with those two clowns while she went out.;    Instead, they
want the new "Baby Talk" to be more like the movie, with Maggie searching for
a father for her child and gradually realizing the guy next door is her ideal
choice.;    Though some viewers may be surprised to find the same baby living
in a new apartment with a new, dark-haired mom this fall, so far there's no
plan for any on-screen explanation of why Maggie looks like a different
person.;    "We thought of a lot of ways to do it," said Orenstein, "like
opening with Mary Page Keller just taking the bandages off and saying: 'I hope
I haven't changed much.' I don't know what we'll do. I don't think America
really cares.";    That may be the one part they've got right so far.  </TEXT>
