<DESCRIPT>  CELEBRITY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  CBS is lining up a stellar list of names for its "Stompin' at the Savoy.";  
We've learned that Lynn Whitfield, Jasmine Guy, Vanessa Williams and Mario Van
Peebles are set to star in the musical drama based in Depression-era Harlem --
and that "Dream Girl" Jennifer Holliday is reportedly in negotiations for a
singing-only portrayal of a young Ella Fitzgerald.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SAVVY LINEUP FOR CBS'S 'SAVOY'  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Grapevine  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "Savoy" is being rushed toward a Jan. 6 production start -- and what a rush
it is. With the network hoping to have the elaborate project ready for spring
airing, producer Richard Maynor and director Debbie Allen aren't getting much
time for holiday cheer. Casting is still under way. Rights to vintage songs
are still being cleared. The crunch of activities is toughest on Allen, who's
been battling the flu while juggling work on her "A Different World" series
with a whirlwind of "Savoy" activities -- including a quick location-scouting
trip to North Carolina. (She's also taking a bit part in the telepic -- as a
hooker.);   SOMETHING NEW: ABC has given a green light to Tony Danza for
production of a reality show pilot to be made by his Katie Face Productions.
As the "Who's the Boss?" hunk has explained the reality offering he hopes to
see as a weekly show, "It'll offer assistance to inner-city kids and will
chronicle their progress." Danza, who considers this the final year for the
7-year-old "Boss," has been talking about serving as narrator of the reality
program. The pilot is expected to shoot in early '92.;   PUTTING ON HIS ACTING
GLOVES: Former heavyweight boxing champ James "Buster" Douglas is in
Vancouver, British Columbia, to film an episode of Stephen J. Cannell's
syndicated "Street Justice" series, which stars Carl Weathers and Bryan
Genesse. In his first acting role, Douglas plays a prison inmate hired by the
mob to kill a friend of Grady's (Genesse) who was recently sent to prison.
Douglas is donating his salary from the show, scheduled to air in February, to
the Lula Pearl Douglas Foundation. He founded the non-profit charity
organization dedicated to helping inner city youth in memory of his mother,
who died two weeks before his February '90 championship bout with Mike Tyson.;
  SNOWBOUND?: Though the casting sign is still lit for "Aspen" and there are
reports that the big-screen story of two ski instructors will roll in
February, producer Leonard Goldberg says "all that has been premature" -- and
that he doesn't even know if the drama will get made.;   From Liz Smith in New
York; I DON'T care what director Tony Bill is telling other columnists. He and
MGM-Pathe wanted Madonna to test for "Baboon Heart." All that's happened since
then is that they reluctantly backed down from their demand after Madonna
refused.;   So it did indeed look as if she would do the movie after getting
her way. But now I hear again she is out of this project, which is to star
Billy Baldwin.;   HERE'S ANOTHER departure from conventional wisdom. Word had
been going around that Bruce Willis and his movie career are all washed up.
Rumor had it that his latest, "The Last Boy Scout," would never pull Bruce's
"Bonfire of the Vanities" and "Hudson Hawk" flops out of the fire. And all
this stuff started before anyone had even seen the new movie.;   Well, I went
to see "The Last Boy Scout" at a sneak preview, and the audience went wild!
This picture is a combo of "Die Hard," "Beverly Hills Cop" and "Lethal
Weapon," and you can add all their sequels, too. I don't see how "The Last Boy
Scout" can fail -- it has the requisite action, violence, cynicism, alienated
people, proper villains, and it has Willis in his Humphrey Bogart phase. Not
bad.;   OK -- so Vanilla Ice's movie, "Cool as Ice," which was supposed to
turn him into "the new Elvis," didn't exactly set off a box-office inferno.
Still, the great white rapper has obviously saved his pennies. Ice recently
closed a deal on an estate on Miami Beach's exclusive Starr Island, where a
"small cottage" runs in the million-dollar range.;   As his neighbor, Ice will
have superstar pop/salsa queen, Gloria Estefan -- just three doors down. Maybe
Estefan can give Ice some tips on how to handle a big career, once you have
one.  </TEXT>
