<SECOND>BC-Fall TV, Adv 01-03,1239</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Comeback' Season Brings More of Same</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This is the first story in a package on the fall TV season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you didn't know better, you'd swear it was
this TV season, not last year's, suffering from the creative woes of
a writers strike.
   The 1989-90 season that officially begins Sept. 18 offers
witches, nuns, inner-city teachers, cute families and buddy cops.
   Very little here hasn't been seen before.
   Alarmingly, there are fewer exceptions to the rule that network
fare must strive to reach new depths of mediocrity. This isn't going
to help the networks stem the audience erosion that has plagued them
in recent years. Who wouldn't rather rent a movie that be stuck with
``Baywatch?''
   In seasons past, previewing the fall shows generally revealed a
few that broke the same-old-stuff mold _ the ``Frank's Places'' and
``Miami Vices'' and ``Hill Street Blueses.''
   Most of this year's new shows range from dismal to mediocre _ BUT
...
   ABC does have the admirable ``Life Goes On,'' a wry and realistic
family drama whose cast includes a real-life Down's syndrome actor
playing a teen-age son who has the condition.
   And CBS has ``The Famous Teddy Z,'' a sophisticated, inside-show
business comedy starring Jon Cryer (``Pretty in Pink'') as a
mail-room nobody instantly elevated to high-powered agent. It was
created by Hugh Wilson, who was owed one by CBS after the network
canceled his critically acclaimed ``Frank's Place.''
   Marcy Carsey and Tom Werner, producers of the hits ``The Cosby
Show,'' ``Roseanne'' and ``A Different World,'' will try to do it
again with ``Chicken Soup,'' on ABC, starring stand-up comic Jackie
Mason as a nice Jewish man having an affair with his Catholic
neighbor, played by Lynn Redgrave.
   And CBS has ``Major Dad,'' a sitcom starring the bankable Gerald
McRaney (``Simon &amp; Simon'') as a macho, right-wing Marine trying to
adjust to married life with a liberal wife (Shanna Reed) and three
step-daughters.
   NBC could break some ground with the political crime drama
``Mancuso, FBI,'' starring Robert Loggia as the burned-out FBI agent
he played in the provocative miniseries ``Favorite Son.''
   And no one can accuse ABC's ``Doogie Howser, M.D.'' of
copy-catting. The half-hour ``dramedy,'' from Steven Bochco (``L.A.
Law,'' ``Hooperman'') revolves around a 16-year-old boy wonder who
is a physician.
   Otherwise, the fall lineup looks like rehashes, also-rans and
sleep aids.
   NBC had little room for improvement, having already pummeled ABC
and CBS for four seasons. But in its effort to seek the perfect
prime-time schedule it has deigned to do some minor tinkering,
adding five new shows. ABC and CBS added nine and eight,
respectively.
   There's NBC's ``Sister Kate,'' starring Stephanie Beacham, former
glamour girl on ``Dynasty,'' who is surprisingly well-cast as a
crotchety nun with a passel of precious urchins.
   ``Nutt House'' is mindless slapstick about an ill-run New York
hotel, starring Harvey Korman and Cloris Leachman. It comes from Mel
Brooks, who teamed with wunderkind Alan Spencer, creator of ``Sledge
Hammer!'' It is paired with ``Night Court,'' which looks like
educational television by comparison.
   What would society do without a network hour devoted to the
emotional involvements of scantily clad lifeguards? NBC has met the
challenge with ``Baywatch,'' sadly the only show on this season from
Mr. Quality Television, Grant Tinker's company.
   Do you miss ``Miami Vice?'' NBC replaces it with another
buddy-cops show. This time, it's old cop-young cop and called
``Hardball.'' Not as much style as ``Vice,'' but good character
possibilities.
   Third-place CBS, which has the greatest need for breakout shows,
has settled instead for a bottom-of-the-barrel ratings ploy,
``Rescue 911,'' a graphic ``reality-based'' show about emergency
calls. It is a throwback to the early days of last season when the
writers strike crippled production of fiction shows and the networks
had to stoop to stuff like this. This season, CBS is putting it on
by choice.
   CBS' ``Island Son'' lured perennial miniseries star Richard
Chamberlain back to series television with a Hawaii locale and a
role as a doctor. It wasn't available for pre-season scrutiny.
   ``The People Next Door,'' a sitcom about a cartoonist and his
family, relies on special effects and apparently hopes to capitalize
on the success of ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit.'' It's an ambitious
attempt, but doesn't work.
   ``Wolf'' stars Jack Scalia in another version of the discredited
cop who becomes a private eye and tries to clear his name. There's
nothing to help viewers pick this one out of a lineup.
   CBS' ``Peaceable Kingdom'' stars the durable Lindsay Wagner as a
remarkably boring zoo administrator. The cheetah is a better actor.
   Stephen Cannell (``Wiseguy,'' ``Hunter'') has a third network
show, ``Top of the Hill,'' starring William Katt (``Greatest
American Hero'') as a long-haired surfer who takes over his ailing
father's congressional seat. Civics 101 was more riveting.
   ``Snoops'' is a screwball mystery-comedy starring Tim and Daphne
Maxwell Reid, former stars of ``Frank's Place.'' He is a professor
of criminology, she is a protocol officer. Nothing was available for
pre-screening, but these are likable stars.
   ABC's ballyhooed deal with Bochco has yielded the questionable
but competent ``Doogie Howser,'' starring Neil Patrick Harris as the
16-year-old genius with a medical license.
   CBS made a little headway with the Western ``Paradise'' last
season. ABC, perhaps inspired more by the success of CBS' ``Lonesome
Dove,'' adds another of the long-missing Western genre, ``The Young
Riders,'' about the Pony Express. It needs better writing.
   ABC has two innocuous spinoffs. From ``Who's the Boss?'' comes
``Living Dolls,'' a sitcom about four teen-aged models sharing an
apartment in New York. Michael Learned stars as their den mother.
The other is ``Family Matters,'' a black family sitcom centered on
the extended family of acerbic elevator operator, Harriette, of
``Perfect Strangers.''
   A writer-producer spun off ABC's ``Head of the Class'' to create
a black ``Welcome Back, Kotter'' in the new ``Homeroom.''
   In ABC's ``Free Spirit'' a housekeeper who's a witch goes to work
for a single father. What comic possibilities!
   To recap, CBS has two good bets in ``Major Dad'' and ``Teddy Z,''
both joining the reasonably successful Monday comedy lineup. But
they'll likely be moved to other nights.
   ABC's ``Life Goes On'' deserves a break and might get one. It's
in a time period opposite the top-10 ``60 Minutes'' and isn't
expected to do boffo numbers, so it might stay around a while.
Critical response should help it.
   ABC's ``Chicken Soup'' is an acquired taste, but it has a cushy
time slot, behind ``Roseanne.'' Hey, a lot of people think Jackie
Mason is very funny.
   Likely goners, due to low quality and-or tough competition,
include ``Homeroom,'' ``Peaceable Kingdom,'' ``Wolf'' and ``Free
Spirit.''
   ``Nutt House'' could get a cult following of over-medicated
viewers, but don't bet on it.
   The rest of the pack merit little more than a shrug.
   So there you have one of the reasons that almost two-thirds of
homes with televisions also have cable and why a third of viewers
opted for something other than network programs last season.
   This season, those people will pay their cable bills happily.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>

