<HEAD>Man Accused of Bothering Child TV Star Dies After Drinking
Pesticide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUINN LOTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of mailing sexually explicit
letters to the child star of the ``Who's the Boss?'' television
show died 11 days after drinking a pesticide, authorities said
Saturday.
   A postmortem examination determined that Mark A. Budman, 28, of
Carson died of pneumonia and respiratory failure caused by
malathion poisoning, said David Campbell, coroner's supervising
investigator.
   Campbell said Budman's death was a suicide.
   Budman was pronounced dead Thursday at Harbor-UCLA Medical
Center in Torrance, said Sheriff's Deputy Patrick Hunter. Budman
was admitted to the hospital's intensive care unit July 8 after
drinking malathion, Hunter said.
   Budman had previously tried to kill himself, authorities said.
   The man drank a quart of malathion, said Deputy City Attorney
Alice Hand, who was prosecuting Budman in connection with
harassment of actor Danny Pintauro.
   The prosecutor said Budman was charged June 7 with two
misdemeanor counts of sending ``bizarre letters featuring sexual
acts,'' to Pintauro, who plays Jonathan Bower on the ABC-TV show
starring Tony Danza. On the series, Danza plays housekeeper to
executive Angela Bower and Jonathan, her teen-age son.
   Letters and cassette tapes were sent to the young actor from
March 1 to May 31, the prosecutor said. A warrant was issued after
Budman failed to appear for a July 12 court date.
   Malathion is a commonly used pesticide available at most garden
shops, hardware stores and nurseries.
   State agriculture officials have been spraying a syrup laced
with malathion over parts of Southern California periodically for
nearly a year in an effort to wipe out a Mediterranean fruit fly
infestation.
   The spraying has prompted angry protests from residents
complaining about the potential risks to public health, and several
cities have tried unsuccessfully to halt the nighttime helicopter
missions.
   Agriculture officials maintain that the pesticide is diluted to
such small amounts that the aerial application is safe.
</TEXT>
