<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tony Danza, the former professional boxer who
stars in TV's ``Who's The Boss?'' comedy series, says he was humbled
by getting a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
   ``I don't deserve this, when I see all the talented people out
there who don't have one,'' Danza told fans Monday. ``But being a
kid from New York, I couldn't resist my name in the sidewalk.''
   Danza gained fame as an aspiring boxer moonlighting as a cabbie
in the TV series ``Taxi.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood stars today are ``sort of a strange
breed'' who really don't know how to dress well, says Rodeo Drive
dress shop owner Herbert Fink.
   ``Some of them reach stardom very quickly. Quite often they're
from small, unsophisticated areas, so they really have no idea of
how to dress. They wear the wrong colors, the wrong styles. They
have all this money and they almost don't know how to spend it,'' he
said in this week's TV Guide.
   ``Dynasty'' designer Nolan Miller agreed. Asked to name six
Hollywood women with class and taste, Miller could only come up with
two from his show: Diahann Carroll and Linda Evans.
   ``All you have to do is catch a plane to see how far fashion has
gone downhill,'' he said. ``You see actresses in jogging suits.''
   But ``Wheel of Fortune'' co-host Vanna White said fans prefer the
casual look.
   ``They think I'm a real person,'' she said. ``I mean, I wear nice
sweats. I'm presentable. And I think it's great because stars are
humans, just like everybody else.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pauline Collins, who played the saucy maid on TV's
``Upstairs, Downstairs,'' has been named best actress on the London
stage for her one-woman comedy ``Shirley Valentine.''
   Alex Jennings and Tom Wilkinson tied for best actor in awards
presented by Drama magazine.
   David Hare's ``The Secret Rapture,'' due off-Broadway in May, was
named best play for 1988, and a revival of the musical ``South
Pacific'' was honored as best musical.
   Vanessa Redgrave was best supporting actress for her performance
as Nora Melody in a revival of Eugene O'Neill's ``A Touch of the
Poet.'' Best supporting actor went to Peter Lindford, who played
Mephistopheles in a west London production of Goethe's epic
``Faust.''
   Jennings won for his starring role in the Russian satire ``Too
Clever By Half'' and Wilkinson for Ibsen's ``An Enemy of the
People.''
   The quarterly published by the British Theater Association
recently announced the winners, which were decided by a committee of
theater critics and journalists.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Charles is taking his campaign for more
sensitive building design into the book stores with the publication
of ``A Vision of Britain, A Personal View of Architecture.''
   Royalties from the book, based on the Prince of Wales' recent
television program on architecture, will be given to his Charities'
Trust along with a $543,000 advance.
   Doubleday U.K., a division of the Transworld Publishers Ltd.,
said it will publish the hardcover book in Britain in March. It also
will be released in Canada, Australia, New Zealand and the United
States.
   In the Oct. 29 TV documentary, which he wrote himself and
appeared in, Prince Charles said some urban developers were
inflicting ``terrible damage'' on city landscapes.
   The 40-year-old heir to the British throne said they should
listen more to the views of ordinary people and what they wanted
when building the nation's inner cities.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's only a series of simple ``hellos,'' but
when the greeters include President Reagan, Rajiv Gandhi and Prince
Charles among others, two Nebraska brothers think it can add up to
world peace.
   ``I guess when you get the heads of states of 100 countries
together on anything you have really accomplished something,'' said
Michael McCormack, who along with his 31-year-old brother, Brian,
started World Hello Day 15 years ago.
   More than 100 world leaders have passed along greetings of
``hello'' and peace this year, including Reagan, Prime Minister
Gandhi of India and Israeli President Chaim Herzog, McCormack said
Monday.
   McCormack, 36, was attending Harvard University in 1973 when he
and Brian started World Hello Day in response to the growing tension
in the Middle East.
   Others who have participated in World Hello Day include Pope John
Paul II, Mother Teresa, Bishop Desmond Tutu, Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa, the late Egyptian President Anwar Sadat, Costa Rican
President Oscar Arias Sanchez, Queen Elizabeth II and former
Presidents Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ballet dancer Mikhail Baryshnikov is making
his theatrical debut at Duke University as a man who turns into an
insect in Franz Kafka's horrific novella, ``The Metamorphosis.''
   Ron Kumin, Duke's drama administrative director, said he was
approached by producers of the pre-Broadway production because
Baryshnikov wanted a ``less traditional, more relaxed'' setting for
his dramatic debut.
   Baryshnikov, whose film credits include ``The Turning Point'' and
``White Nights,'' will make his stage debut Feb. 3. Performances of
the play, co-produced by Roger Stevens and Lars Schmidt, will run
through Feb. 25, Kumin said this week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arizona Attorney General Bob Corbin, sporting a
four-day growth of beard, mounted a horse to play a role in the
television series ``Unsolved Mysteries.''
   Corbin's hobby, searching for the Lost Dutchman gold mine in the
Superstition Mountains, led to the role in a segment about the death
of Walt Gassler, who may have discovered the 19th-century mine.
   Corbin and a friend, Tom Kollenborn of Apache Junction, were
filmed last weekend making a mock search for the mine, which
included a visit to a re-creation of Gassler's camp.
   The segment is tentatively scheduled for broadcast in February.
</TEXT>
