<DESCRIPT>  TELEVISION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  (box) THE MAN IN THE FAMILY; 9:30 p.m. Wednesday, Chs. 7, 11, 13  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WHY DOES TV HAVE IT OUT FOR ITALIANS?  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Television  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   I WONDER what the Italians ever did to television. Because television has
certainly been taking its revenge on them ever since.;    This has been going
on so long that most viewers probably take it for granted. I did until I got a
call the other day from a reader who asked, "Why do they make Italians look so
bad on TV?";    I don't know, I told her. I guess they want to keep up with
the movies.;    Seriously, the complaint about the movies is that they make
all Italians look like mobsters. On television, they just make them look
stupid.;    Of course, TV makes almost everyone look stupid. I guess the
thinking is that we'll all feel better about ourselves if we watch people who
are dumber than we are.;    But television seems to go out of its way to make
that point when it comes to Italians.;    It's happening again with a summer
sitcom on ABC called "The Man in the Family" (9:30 Wednesdays, Chs. 7, 11,
13), not to be confused with the equally dumb but non-ethnic "Family Man" on
CBS.;    If you haven't had the misfortune of running across "The Man in the
Family" yet, all you've missed is another raucous Italian family yelling at
each other and plodding through life.;    If you saw "The Fanelli Boys" or
"Top of the Heap" this season or dreck like "The Montefuscos" long ago, you've
seen "The Man in the Family.";    The drill here is that Dad dies before the
first commercial, and sonny boy (Ray Sharkey) comes back to run the family
deli and get bossed around by his mom and sister, when he isn't listening to
his dumber-than-dirt pals and their harebrained schemes.;    Sitcom Italian
women are always bossy. Sitcom Italian men are always loud and scheming. The
number of dimensions for either is usually two.;    Now, Italians aren't the
only cardboard characters on TV, but there are probably more cardboard Italian
families on the tube than there are of any other ethnicity.;    I'm not sure
why, but an Italian friend is probably right when he points out that there's
no Italian B'nai B'rith or NAACP. What organized protests there have been were
usually focused on the recurring mob stereotypes.;    It is easier,
apparently, to construct a realistic yet humorous view of Italian-American
home life in a one-shot movie such as "Moonstruck" than in a continuing TV
series. I say that because the former has been successfully done, and the
latter hasn't.;    Oh, sure, there have been good Italian characters on TV.;  
 Columbo was one of them, even if he was played by Peter Falk, who is Jewish.;
   "Petrocelli" was about an Italian lawyer so good even Archie Bunker, whose
legal preference was for folks named Cohen, might have felt he was in good
hands, though he would have mispronounced the barrister's name.;    Vinnie
Terranova on "Wiseguy" was another multi-dimensional character who happened to
be Italian. So were Robert Blake's "Baretta" and Tony Musante's "Toma.";   
Back in the '70s, Vincent Gardenia's Frank Lorenzo on "All in the Family" and
Richard Castellano's Joe Girelli on "The Super" were two fellows who made you
laugh without making you cringe, no matter what your ethnicity.;    On the
other hand, Castellano's "Joe and Sons" a few years later was hideous in its
stereotypic portrayals, despite his best efforts.;    Sometimes even
stereotypes can seem funny instead of offensive, if well done. The Italian
friend I mentioned earlier cracks up at the mere mention of Mr. Bacciagalupe,
who was as stereotypic an Italian vegetable vendor as you could imagine, on
the "Abbott and Costello Show" in the early '50s.;    "You were just assaulted
by Mr. Bacciagalupe," my friend recalls. "He was so funny you couldn't be
offended, because you were paralyzed with laughter.";    My pal hasn't been
laughing much lately at people with names like his on the tube. Paralyzed by
the stupidity of it all might be a better description for his reaction to "The
Man of the Family.";    Maybe next season, which coincides with the 500th
anniversary of one of Italy's most famous son's journey to the New World,
television might wise up and give us Italians we can laugh with, instead of
at.;    In the meantime, perhaps the best defense for all of us against sludge
like "The Man in the Family" is to change the channel.;    Or possibly to go
on vacation, which I'm doing at this very moment. See you in August.  </TEXT>
