<HEAD>`Brady Christmas' Gives CBS Second Place</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS got a ``A Very Brady Christmas'' gift when
the reunion movie featuring the 1970s sitcom family was No. 2 in the
A.C. Nielsen Co. television ratings, giving CBS its first week out
of third place this season.
   NBC firmly won the week anyway, and ``The Cosby Show'' was the
No. 1 show last week.
   As of Saturday, CBS was still in third place in the Nielsens, but
Sunday's ``A Very Brady Christmas'' was the highest-rated
made-for-TV movie so far this season, with a rating of 25.1 and a 39
share, and boosted CBS into second place. The sitcom ``The Brady
Bunch'' ran on ABC from 1969-1974 and has a cult following in reruns.
   ``The Cosby Show'' had a rating of 25.9 and a 42 share. The rest
of the top 10 were: ``A Different World,'' NBC; ``Cheers,'' NBC;
``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC; ``Golden Girls,'' NBC;
``L.A. Law,'' NBC; ``Murder, She Wrote,'' CBS; and ``Dear John,''
NBC, tied with ``60 Minutes,'' CBS.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 homes with television. The
share is a percentage of sets in use.
   NBC won the week ending Dec. 18 with an average prime-time rating
of 15.4. CBS had a 13.1 and ABC an 11.8.
   ``ABC World News Tonight'' was the top-rated news show last week,
with an average rating of 11.0 and a 20 share. ``NBC Nightly News''
had a 10.9 and 20, edging the ``CBS Evening News,'' which had a 10.7
and 19.
   The only other new holiday movie last week, NBC's nostalgic
``I'll Be Home for Christmas,'' also did well, ranking 15th.
   CBS' ``Wiseguy'' came in 32nd, apparently getting a boost from
guest star Jerry Lewis, who will appear in a continuing storyline
for several episodes of the crime drama.
   NBC's constroverial episode of ``Midnight Caller,'' about a San
Francisco man with AIDS purposely engaging in high-risk sex, ranked
33rd, doing no worse or better than it has so far this season. AIDS
organizations and gay-rights groups had protested the episode,
saying it promoted antagonism against AIDS victims.
   ABC's touted exercise in kiddie glasnost, ``Free to Be a
Family,'' a joint U.S.-Soviet broadcast, ranked 58th.
   The lowest-rated network shows of the week were: ``Davy
Crockett,'' ``Mission Impossible,'' ``Moscow Circus,'' ``Annie
McGuire,'' ``West 57th,'' ``Simon &amp; Simon,'' ``TV101,'' ``Murphy's
Law,'' ``Knightwatch'' and ``Burning Issues.''
</TEXT>
