<HEAD>CBS Seeks TV Comeback, Fox Expands Schedule To Five Nights</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 15th graf, `CBS' new ...' to CORRECT title of show to
`Four Alarm Family' sted of `Four Alarm Fire.'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-TV-Fall Schedules-List</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS, trying to battle back from three seasons as
third in evening TV ratings, said Tuesday it will have nine new
series next fall. Fox Broadcasting said it'll go to a
five-night-a-week schedule.
   Fox also said it is moving the hit ``The Simpsons'' to head-on
Thursday competition with NBC's ``The Cosby Show.''
   And Fox's shows will air on Thursdays-through Mondays. It had
been expected to add Wednesdays and Fridays to its current
Saturday-through-Monday lineup.
   Fox, which also said it would air a new Sunday sitcom about an
interracial marriage called ``True Colors,'' announced nine new
series. To make room, it axed one of its original series, ``21 Jump
Street,'' and such others as ``Alien Nation,'' ``Booker,'' and
``The Outsiders.''
   CBS' new lineup, which includes a comic-book hero and an action
series whose heroes fight polluters, was described by CBS
Entertainment president Jeff Sagansky as a starting move in the
network's road to ratings recovery.
   ``This is a strong first step in the process of rebuilding our
prime time lineup,'' said Sagansky. The schedule, his first full
one since CBS hired him last fall, revamps all nights but Tuesday
and Sunday.
   It also gives CBS four nights of comedies.
   The goal, he told CBS affiliates in a closed-circuit hookup, is
to attract younger viewers and more family viewing in the 8 p.m.
EDT time period.
   Speaking with reporters here later, he discounted suggestions
that CBS' new schedule is not as unconventional as ABC's and CBS'.
   It's the way a show is done, not the idea for it, that makes it
succeed, he said: ``What makes a show unconventional is the way
it's executed, not cops singing or whatever is behind `Twin Peaks.'
''
   CBS' roster includes five new hour-long series; four new sitcoms
and a comedy once on NBC, ``The Hogan Family.'' It also has a
pre-cable movie package of such hits as ``Born on the Fourth of
July'' and ``Do The Right Thing.''
   The low-rated ``Saturday Night With Connie Chung'' will move to
Mondays with a different format and name _ ``Face to Face With
Connie Chung.'' Two test runs of the new version got high ratings
during the May ratings sweeps.
   But CBS axed the Vietnam War series ``Tour of Duty,'' the
venerable ``Falcon Crest,'' whose demise was announced last week,
and such far newer ones as ``The Famous Teddy Z,'' ``City'' and
``Sydney.''
   However, Sagansky said ``Paradise'' may be renewed. ``Wiseguy''
now is in backup status, he added, with Ken Wahl to return in the
first few episodes, then be succeeded by Stephen Bauer, who would
play a new undercover agent.
   CBS' new sitcoms are the movie spinoff ``Uncle Buck,'' the
blue-collar ``Lenny,'' ``Four Alarm Family,'' about a widowed
firefighter with four kids, and ``Evening Shade,'' starring Burt
Reynolds as an ex-football star who moves his family back to the
small Arkansas town of his boyhood.
   Edward Woodward of CBS' late ``The Equalizer'' will return in
the hour-long ``Over My Dead Body'' as a burnt-out novelist paired
with a young obituary writer played by Jessica Lundy.
   CBS' other new hour-long entries are ``The Flash,'' based on the
comic book crime-fighter; ``WIOU,'' about the cutthroat world of
local TV, and ``The Hammersmiths,'' a family drama with Lucie Arnaz.
   There also will be ``The Green Machine,'' the first network
drama in which the good guys battle those who would harm planet
Earth.
   In addition to ``True Colors,'' Fox's other sitcoms are ``Parker
Lewis Can't Lose,'' about high school life; ``Get a Life,''
starring Chris Elliott as a 30-year-old newspaper delivery boy;
``Good Grief,'' about undertaking; and ``Babes,'' about three
sisters in a cramped New York apartment.
   There also is a half-hour serious series, ``American
Chronicles,'' by Mark Frost and David Lynch, creators of ``Twin
Peaks,'' and an hour series of various video projects, ``Fox Video
Hour.''
   The other new hour-long series are ``Class of Beverly Hills,''
about a Midwestern family moving to Southern California;
``D.E.A.,'' about exploits of the Drug Enforcement Administration,
and ``Against the Law,'' about an unconventional trial lawyer.
   Fox also added a two-hour Monday movie night, ``Fox Night at the
Movies.''
   Fox says it has 129 affiliates, compared with the more than 200
each of CBS, NBC and ABC. But it isn't officially considered a
network yet by the Federal Communications Commission.
   Its expansion this fall was made possible by a one-year FCC
waiver that lets it broadcast 18{ hours a week of prime-time
programming without being subject to restrictions that bar CBS, NBC
and ABC from the lucrative syndication business.
</TEXT>
