PHOTO: Omri Katz spreads the news in 'Eerie, Indiana.'  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  FALL; TELEVISION; PROGRAM; REVIEW; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IT USUALLY takes a few weeks to know if a new TV series is really worth
watching regularly. But, while you're waiting, we thought you might like some
capsule opinions of the 29 new fall shows on the four commercial broadcast
networks.;   The following mini-reviews are, in most cases, based on our
viewing of one or more complete episodes. Exceptions are noted. Ratings are
from a low of one to a high of four stars.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  TV Magazine  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  A LOOK AT THE NEW SHOWS
PROGRAMS TO SEEK OUT OR TO AVOID  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Fall Preview / Mini-Reviews  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  The Adventures of Mark; and Brian; NBC, Sundays, 7-7:30 p.m.; (star)(star);  
This show is built around real-life Los Angeles radio personalities Mark
Thompson and Brian Phelps, two "irrepressible" characters whose antics border
on the outrageous techniques of "shock radio." Each week they'll live out
their personal fantasies, such as becoming trapeze artists in a circus or
performing in concert with the Temptations. Previews this Monday and Thursday
nights at 8:30; premieres next Sunday.; Best of the Worst; Fox, Saturdays,
9:30-10 p.m.; (star) 1/2;   This "reality" show concentrates on real-life
stuff that's so bad it's funny -- or at least ought to be. Like the singing
career of William Shatner. Already premiered.; Brooklyn Bridge; CBS, Fridays,
8:30-9 p.m.; (Not available for preview);   Gary David Goldberg, creator of
"Family Ties," takes us back to Brooklyn, N.Y., circa 1956, for this nostalgic
situation comedy about an extended family at a time when an American era was
changing. Starring Marion ("Happy Days") Ross. Premieres Sept. 20 at 8 p.m.
with a special one-hour episode. Moves to its regular time slot Sept. 27.; The
Carol Burnett Show; CBS, Fridays, 9-10 p.m.; (Not available for preview);  
NBC didn't want Burnett's "Carol &amp; Co." half-hour show back this fall, despite
reasonable ratings; so Burnett was snapped up by CBS, which will offer her in
a new comedy/variety show with a new ensemble, hoping for a repeat of her
original success on the network a decade ago when her hour was one of TV's
most popular. Premieres in October.; The Commish; ABC, Saturdays, 10-11 p.m.;
(star)(star);   Michael Chiklis, who played the late John Belushi in the movie
"Wired," is big-city police commissioner Tony Scali, a rough-edged but likable
human dumpling who sings operatic solos while shaving. Naturally, he has a
warmly human "hands-on" approach to police work. Theresa Saldana co-stars as
Tony's wife, Rachel, in this character-oriented, action drama from Stephen J.
Cannell ("Hunter," "Wiseguy"). Premieres Saturday, Sept. 28, at 9 p.m. with a
two-hour episode, then moves to its 10 o'clock slot Oct. 5.; Drexell's Class;
Fox, Thursdays, 8:30-9 p.m.; (Not available for preview);   Call it
"Kindergarten Cop: The Next Generation." Dabney Coleman, the guy you loved to
hate in "Buffalo Bill" and "The 'Slap' Maxwell Story," returns as Otis
Drexell, who agrees to teach a fourth-grade class instead of going to prison
for tax evasion. Premieres Sept. 19.; Eerie, Indiana; NBC, Sundays, 7:30-8
p.m.; (star)(star)(star);   This fantasy series takes place in the weirdest
town in the United States -- yep, it's even weirder than Twin Peaks -- where
13-year-old Marshall Teller (Omri Katz) and sidekick Simon Holmes (Justin
Shenkarow) can't seem to convince their folks anything weird is going on.
Funny, bizarre and frequently directed by "consultant" Joe Dante ("Gremlins,"
"The Howling"). Premieres next Sunday.; FBI: The Untold Stories; ABC,
Thursdays, 9-9:30 p.m.; (star)(star);   Pernell Roberts ("Bonanza," "Trapper
John, M.D.") hosts and narrates this latest fact-based series drawn from FBI
files. News footage and even interviews with the real officers and criminal
suspects are supplemented with dramatic re-enactments. Premieres Sept. 26.;
Flesh 'n' Blood; NBC, Fridays, 9:30-10 p.m.; (star)(star)(star) 1/2;  
Baltimore D.A. Rachel Brennan (Lisa Darr) wants to locate the mom who gave her
up for adoption years ago but, instead, discovers the brother she didn't know
she had -- Arlo Weed (David Keith), a hillbilly con man, who brings along his
two kids and moves in with her. Wild and funny. Previews Thursday, Sept. 19,
at 10 p.m. Premieres Sept. 20.; Good and Evil; ABC, Wednesdays, 10:30-11 p.m.;
(star)(star);   If you notice familiar traces of "Soap" on this absurdist
sitcom, blame it on creator Susan Harris, who also dreamed up that legendary
1970s sitcom. Margaret Whitton is the "good" sister, a widow being courted by
a clumsy blind man as well as the two-timing boyfriend of her sexy "evil"
sister, Teri Garr, whose own husband, long believed dead, is thawing out after
four years in an ice crevasse. Goofy, mean-spirited, but frequently funny.
Premieres Sept. 25.; Homefront; ABC, Tuesdays, 10-11 p.m.; (star)(star)(star);
  Men returning from overseas duty in World War II try to resume their lives
in a small Ohio town in 1945 in this drama series that explores today's issues
through the perspective of yesterday. Featuring a large ensemble cast, mostly
newcomers. Not a soap opera, though it comes from David Jacobs, the creator of
"Dallas," and the current producers of "Knots Landing," Bernard Lechowick and
Lynn Marie Latham. Premieres Sept. 24 at 9:30 with a 90-minute episode, then
moves to its regular 10 o'clock berth Oct. 1.; Home Improvement; ABC,
Tuesdays, 8:30-9 p.m.; (star)(star)(star);   Stand-up comic Tim Allen brings
his "tool talk" and Robert Bly-style, pro-male routines to TV in the role of
Tim Taylor, host of a cable-TV do-it-yourself show along the lines of PBS's
"This Old House." Co-starring Patricia Richardson as wife Jill, who undermines
his status as America's "manly man" of the '90s. Premieres Sept. 17.; I'll Fly
Away; NBC, Tuesdays, 8-9 p.m.; (star)(star)(star) 1/2;   This one-hour drama
from the creators of "St. Elsewhere," "A Year in the Life" and "Northern
Exposure" takes place in the American South in the mid-1950s, just as the
civil rights era was beginning. Forrest Bedford (Sam Waterston) is a
principled lawyer, trying to raise his three kids in turbulent times with the
help of his troubled black housekeeper, Lilly Harper (Regina Taylor). Previews
Oct. 7 with a two-hour special and moves into its regular one-hour time slot
Oct. 8.; Herman's Head; Fox, Sundays, 9:30-10 p.m.; (star)(star)(star);  
William Ragsdale is Herman, an ambitious young man struggling to get ahead in
the corporate world. But this innovative sitcom also takes us inside his head,
which is peopled with imaginary characters. Premieres tonight.; Man of the
People; NBC, Sundays, 8-8:30 p.m.; (star)(star)(star);   James Garner shines
in his first sitcom, playing con artist Jim Doyle, who's appointed to fill out
his ex-wife's unexpired city council term and winds up serving the people
while trying to bilk the city. Co-starring Corinne Bohrer, Kate Mulgrew,
George Wyner. Very promising. Premieres next Sunday.; Nurses; NBC, Saturdays,
9:30-10 p.m.; (star)(star);   The prolific Susan Harris ("Soap," "Golden
Girls") wasn't content to create just ABC's "Good &amp; Evil" this season. She
also concocted this ensemble comedy about five nurses in a big-city hospital.
Lots of sarcasm, especially from perpetually P.O.-ed Stephanie Hodge as the
recently divorced nurse, Sandy. Premieres Saturday.; Pacific Station; NBC,
Sundays, 8:30-9 p.m.; (star)(star);   This low-brow "Barney Miller" is an
ensemble comedy in a police precinct in wacky Venice, Calif. It's anchored by
the skilled Robert Guillaume ("Benson"), who plays a veteran detective saddled
with a new partner (Richard Libertini) fresh from a psychiatric ward. Also
stars Ron Leibman ("Kaz") as a womanizing detective and Ken Epstein ("Grand")
as their incompetent captain. Marginal. Premieres next Sunday.; Palace Guard;
CBS, Fridays, 10-11 p.m.; (star) 1/2;   Master hotel thief Tommy Logan (D.W.
Moffett) is hired by hotel magnate Arturo Taft (Tony LoBianco) to be a
security adviser for the Palace hotel chain. But Tommy has to work with
public-relations woman Christy Cooper (Marcy Walker), a former B-movie queen.
Producer Stephen J. Cannell wants this to be fast and sexy, but it works like
"Moonlighting" on a night with no moon. Premieres in October.; Princesses;
CBS, Fridays, 8-8:30 p.m.; (star) 1/2;   Call it "Golden Girls: The Early
Years." Three single women -- dithery Julie Hagerty, sneery Fran Drescher and
hoity-toity ex-princess Twiggy Lawson -- mistakenly lay claim to the same
Manhattan apartment, then agree to share it and their comic adventures. From
Barry Kemp, creator of "Newhart" and "Coach." Not irresistible. Premieres
Sept. 27.; Pros and Cons; ABC, Thursdays, 8-9 p.m.; (Not available for
preview);   This is a heavily overhauled new edition of last year's "Gabriel's
Fire." Gabriel Bird (James Earl Jones) moves to L.A., where he teams up with
Mitch, a seedy private eye played by Richard Crenna. Landlady Josephine (Madge
Sinclair) also leaves Chicago to keep Bird company. The new show is expected
to be funnier, less dour. Premieres Sept. 26.; P.S. I Luv U; CBS, Saturdays,
10-11 p.m.; (star);   Producer Glen Larson has teamed Connie Sellecca (as a
beautiful con lady) with Greg Evigan (as a tough New York cop) in a ridiculous
action show about an unmarried couple forced to pose as husband and wife,
while they hide out from Mafia hit men in Palm Springs, where they work for
Palm Security Investigations (PSI). Just as awful as it sounds, maybe even
worse. Previews next Sunday at 9 as a two-hour movie; premieres Sept. 21.;
Reasonable Doubts; NBC, Fridays, 10-11 p.m.; (star)(star) 1/2;   Oscar-winner
Marlee Matlin ("Children of a Lesser God") becomes the first hearing-impaired
actor to star in a weekly TV series. She plays Tess Kaufman, a shrewd
assistant D.A., who's teamed with police detective Richard Brandt (Mark
Harmon) because he knows sign language. Their growing relationship offers the
only promise for an otherwise routine law-and-order melodrama. Previews
Thursday, Sept. 26, at 10. Premieres Sept. 27.; Roc; Fox, Sundays, 8:30-9
p.m.; (star)(star)(star);   Charles Dutton, star of Broadway's "The Piano
Lesson," plays garbage collector Roc Emerson in this promising series about a
black family. Already premiered.; Royal Family; CBS, Wednesdays, 8-8:30 p.m.;
(star)(star)(star);   This isn't about the Windsors of Buckingham Palace but a
black family in Atlanta. Redd Foxx is just-retired mailman Al Royal, and Della
Reese is his sarcastic wife, Victoria. They're trying to cope with their new
semi-permanent guests -- their husband-less daughter and her three young kids.
Some riotous rancor. Premieres Sept. 18.; Sibs; ABC, Wednesdays, 9:30-10 p.m.;
(Not available for preview);   Sibs is short for siblings, which, in this
case, means three sisters (Marsha Mason, Margaret Colin, Jami Gertz) whose
comic relationships form the story line for this ensemble piece from the
producers of "The Mary Tyler Moore Show," "Taxi" and "The Simpsons." Also
starring Emmy-winner Alex Rocco ("The Famous Teddy Z"). Previews Tuesday,
Sept. 17, at 9:30; premieres Sept. 25.; Step by Step; ABC, Fridays, 8:30-9
p.m.; (star)(star)(star);   This unlikely sitcom pairs comic actress Suzanne
Somers ("Three's Company") with Patrick Duffy ("Dallas"), who's trying his
first sitcom role. They're newlyweds whose kids from their earlier marriages
don't get along at all. Surprisingly likable. Premieres Sept. 20.; Teech; CBS,
Wednesdays, 8:30-9 p.m.; (star);   Ugandan comic Phill Lewis stars as the
music teacher who leaves rough South Philly for a job teaching obnoxious white
boys in a private boarding school. Lots of obnoxiousness but few laughs.
Premieres Sept. 18.; The Torkelsons; NBC, Saturdays, 8:30-9 p.m.;
(star)(star)(star)(star);   This could be the season's most pleasant surprise:
a sitcom about a poor Oklahoma family held together by a hard-working,
eccentric mom (Connie Ray) and viewed from the perspective of a dreamy
14-year-old (Olivia Burnette), who may be the season's brightest new star.
Utterly charming. Premieres Sept. 21.; The Ultimate Challenge; Fox, Fridays,
9-10 p.m.; (Not available for preview);   Mike Adamle and Heather Thomas are
the co-hosts of this stunt-oriented "reality" show, which promises to be a
bastard child of "That's Incredible!" It's just the thing for those who can't
wait to see somebody bungee-jump off the Empire State Building. Premieres
Friday night. (box)  </TEXT>
