<HEAD>Rapper, `Spy' Magazine Series Potential New Shows for NBC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC, heading for its fifth consecutive season as
first in the prime-time ratings, is considering a new comedy series
featuring rap singer Fresh Prince and a show based on the satirical
magazine Spy.
   ``We're number one and we intend to stay there,'' NBC
Entertainment president Brandon Tartikoff said Thursday.
   The fall schedules for NBC and its rivals won't be set and
announced until May, but Tartikoff unveiled his development roster
to whip up advertisers' enthusiasm for potential projects.
   CBS and ABC held similar sessions Wednesday.
   NBC's list of prime-time hopefuls, some of which will get a
spring and summer tryout, include a Quincy Jones comedy series with
the rap-music star, a comedy based on the ``Archie'' comic strip
and a new version of the gothic soap opera ``Dark Shadows.''
   Also on the list of prospects are two comedy specials. One,
``The Jackie Bison Show,'' would be a cartoon spoof of show
business and star the first bison ever to host its own TV show.
   The other, a TV version of the satirical magazine Spy, will get
its first on-air shot April 18. The theme will be ``How to Be
Famous.''
   Tartikoff, who spoke to advertising representatives at NBC
offices in Burbank, told reporters afterward he thought that two of
NBC's top money-earners, Bill Cosby and Johnny Carson, would be
back next season.
   The Burbank meeting was shown at NBC offices in New York on a
closed-circuit line.
   NBC is renegotiating a contract that would return the hit ``The
Cosby Show'' for a seventh season, Tartikoff said. He didn't
elaborate on what the renegotiations involved.
   Talks also are under way with Carson, host of the ``Tonight''
show since October 1962. ``We fully expect that Johnny will be
back,'' Tartikoff said.
   NBC, which earlier renewed ``Dear John,'' said it was renewing
five other series _ ``Unsolved Mysteries,'' ``Empty Nest,''
``Midnight Caller,'' ``Quantum Leap'' and ``In the Heat of the
Night.''
   In earlier presentations in Los Angeles, third-place CBS said it
had 23 series pilots under consideration, while ABC's roster of
hopefuls showed 13 comedies, 15 hourlong dramas and two half-hour
dramas.
   Under consideration at NBC are 13 dramas, 17 comedies and nine
miniseries.
   The CBS comedy pilots include ``Sunday Dinner'' from producer
Norman Lear, whose sometimes controversial sitcoms were mainstays
of CBS in the 1970s, and ``Steel Magnolias,'' a small-screen
version of the hit movie of the same name.
   ABC's possible series include Stephen Bochco's one-hour ``Cop
Rock,'' which juxtaposes music and crime-fighting, and a sitcom,
``Dr. Ruth's House,'' starring the veteran dispenser of sex advice,
Dr. Ruth Westheimer.
</TEXT>
