<DESCRIPT>  TELEVISION; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  RANDOM thoughts about a specific medium:;    Pretty sneaky of Michael Gartner
to get in the name of the woman who says she was raped at the Kennedy compound
during his appearance on "Nightline" the other night.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NAMING NAMES, AWAITING THE SWEEPS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Television  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The NBC news president mentioned her last name not once, but twice while
being interviewed by Ted Koppel on the ABC show, which began with one of that
network's vice presidents explaining why its policies prohibited revealing the
name.;    All of which allowed "NBC Nightly News" executive producer Steve
Friedman to go on a New York radio show the next day and say his network
wasn't the only one giving the woman's name -- ABC had done it on "Nightline,"
too.;    He didn't say, of course, that the reason you heard her name on ABC
was that his boss had uttered it.;    Why didn't he say that? No one asked
him.;    Sure, Steve. No one asked the woman if they could use her name,
either, and that's the whole point.;    Interesting, isn't it, that in this
whole debate, none of the voices we hear coming from the networks are women.; 
  The reporter on the original NBC story was Lisa Myers, but she wouldn't say
how she felt about it in a phone call to her the day after the piece ran.;   
HERE'S THE LAW -- Yes, yes, "L.A. Law" will be back with a new episode next
week. The resurrection of Rosalind was just a two-week thing necessitated by
trying to stretch the 22 original episodes into the Nielsen sweeps in May,
which, because of Memorial Day, start April 25.;    The sweeps end May 22,
which is why the last "L.A. Law" of the season is set for May 16.;   
Stretching for sweeps is also why so many other shows have been in reruns the
last couple weeks as well. Now you know.;    HERE'S THE BOSS -- Do you also
know what the longest-running entertainment show on ABC is? No, not "Twin
Peaks," whose many appearances and re-appearances only make it seem like it's
been on forever.;    Actually, the correct answer is "Who's the Boss?," which
has just been renewed for an eighth season. The only comedy around longer is
"Cheers," which will come back for a 10th season on NBC next fall. With the
cancellation of "Dallas," the only drama with a longer run will be CBS's
"Knots Landing.";    It also means that "Who's the Boss?" will make it at
least twice as long on the same network as Tony Danza's first show, the
infinitely better "Taxi.";    Maybe that's why ABC's slogan (or any of the
other network's) has never been, "Quality is Job One.";    ANOTHER ONE BITES
THE DUST -- The quality of CBS News continues to drop with the ham-fisted cuts
going on.;    Joan Snyder, the first female field producer in CBS history, got
the ax as part of the ongoing layoffs that will hit about 120 staffers across
the ever-shrinking news department.;    She is now a producer for "Sunday
Morning," but in her 30 years at the network, she wrote for such luminaries as
Walter Cronkite, Mike Wallace and Harry Reasoner, in addition to paving the
way for the women who followed her by becoming a producer in 1967.;    The way
things are going at the networks these days, better to be an inexperienced
rookie with a puny paycheck than someone who actually knows what he or she is
doing and is paid accordingly.;    LOCAL STUFF -- You may have noticed KRON
(Ch. 4) has new graphics and a new logo in a bright red circle. I guess Red
Ball Movers wasn't using theirs any more. . . .;    KOFY (Ch. 20) has started
simulcasting in Spanish, carrying "Little House on the Prairie," "The A-Team,"
"Bonanza" and "Small Wonder" in two languages.;    Only those who have a
stereo TV can get the shows in Spanish, however, by pushing the secondary
audio programming button. . . .;    For those of you in a buying mood, the
KTEH (Ch. 54) auction got under way Friday and will run through next
Saturday.;    Somewhere in the neighborhood of $850,000 worth of goodies has
been donated by local merchants and individuals. The money raised accounts for
nearly 10 percent of the station's operating budget.;    Last year's auction,
which brought in $368,000, was the 12th largest in the public broadcasting
system and won PBS's National Auction Achievement Award. Station officials say
the goal this year is $425,000.  </TEXT>
