PHOTO: The original second banana: Art Carney's Ed Norton in 'The
Honeymooners.'; PHOTO: Bit player Winkler eventually took over 'Happy Days.';
PHOTO: Estelle Getty won an Emmy as an even older 'Golden Girl.'; PHOTO:
Meshach Taylor co-stars on 'Designing Women.'; PHOTO: Jerry Van Dyke crashed
on 'Car,' wins on 'Coach.'; PHOTO: Laurie Metcalf helps give 'Roseanne' its
bite.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  SUPPORT; TELEVISION; CELEBRITY; CHANGE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WHEN ABC's "Happy Days" began its phenomenally successful run on the network
in 1974, you had to be extra alert to catch a glimpse of Henry Winkler as a
greasy biker named Arthur Fonzarelli.;    But by the time "Happy Days" went
off the air 10 years later, Winkler was the unquestioned star of the show, and
"The Fonz" was such a part of Americana that his leather jacket was presented
to the Smithsonian Institution.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SECOND BANANA REPUBLIC
SUPPORTING ACTORS CAN TAKE OVER THE SHOWS
THEY SUPPORT. HERE ARE 10 OF THE BEST.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Winkler's Fonzie remains a classic example of a supporting character
becoming so crucial to the popularity of a TV show that it was no longer
possible to imagine the show without him.;    Of course, second bananas rarely
"come forward" to take over a show, but it does happen. As a matter of fact,
it happened in 1988, when Jasmine Guy's spoiled Southern student, Whitley
Gilbert, suddenly came forward in the premiere season of NBC's "A Different
World" to obscure Lisa Bonet, who was supposed to be the star of her own
series when her Denise Huxtable character was spun off from NBC's "The Cosby
Show.";    By the second season, Bonet had left the show to have a baby and
eventually took Denise back to "The Cosby Show." Guy's Whitley character, now
much more likable and considerably less spoiled, remains the primary focus of
"A Different World.";    A similar phenomenon now seems to be taking place on
ABC's "Family Matters," where nerdy neighbor Steve Urkel, played by
trumpet-voiced 14-year-old Jaleel White, has come forward to take the
spotlight away from all the original cast members after a one-time guest
appearance last season blossomed into a regular role.;    Most of the time,
though, supporting characters know their place in a series and stay there. But
TV's most skillful second bananas can make those secondary characters so
essential to the overall appeal of a show that they become indispensable, the
way Ken Osmond's Eddie Haskell was in "Leave It to Beaver" or Bob Denver's
Maynard G. Krebs was in "The Many Loves of Dobie Gillis.";    Here's my
personal list of the 10 best second bananas now working in network shows,
playing characters I can't imagine their shows doing without:;    (box)
Katherine Helmond's Mona Robinson in ABC's "Who's the Boss?";    Helmond's
Mona is surely TV's most mischievous mother, a libidinous lady who's not only
always ready for a good time, but also seems to be having one playing this
sexy scamp.;    (box) Estelle Getty's Sophia Petrillo in NBC's "The Golden
Girls.";    Getty was little known to the TV audience when she started playing
Bea Arthur's tactless live-in mom and second banana to three established TV
stars -- Arthur, Rue McClanahan and Betty White -- five seasons ago. Now; For
page 8C; Getty has an Emmy and a host of fans who think she steals the show
from her famous co-stars.;    (box) Meshach Taylor's Anthony Bouvier in CBS's
"Designing Women.";    Stealing scenes from four stars as polished as Dixie
Carter, Delta Burke, Annie Potts and Jean Smart isn't easy for a minor
character who began way in the background, but that's what Taylor does each
week as the kind-hearted, colorful ex-con. Originally just a delivery man
intended as a one-laugh walk-on each week, Anthony is now a partner in the
women's design studio, surely a tribute to Taylor's growing value to this hit
show.;    (box) Jerry Van Dyke's Luther Van Dam in ABC's "Coach.";    People
now can forget Van Dyke starred in what most critics consider the worst sitcom
in TV history: "My Mother, the Car." His lonely, dim-witted Luther, the
incompetent assistant coach, is a brilliant concept brilliantly played by this
long underrated comic actor.;    (box) Max Casella's Vinnie Delpino in ABC's
"Doogie Howser, M.D.";    Casella's inspired work as teen hustler Vinnie, best
pal to prodigy physician Doogie, is so good that it's easy to picture Vinnie
in a show of his own, scoring with "chicks" and setting up deals to make sure
he can afford them. His skill is even more obvious when you realize Casella is
a mature young man in his mid-20s, just pretending to be a 17-year-old.;   
(box) Robert Pastorelli's Eldin Bernecky in CBS's "Murphy Brown.";   
Conceived as little more than a running gag -- the house painter who can't
seem to finish the job -- Eldin has become a key regular on this hit show,
providing celebrity news star Murphy (Candice Bergen) a way to get in touch
with the real world each week. Pastorelli has turned Eldin into a refreshingly
direct, engagingly warm, blue-collar philosopher. Many think his bear-like
Eldin might be a good mate for Murphy, if she ever decides to try matrimony
again.;    (box) David Leisure's Charley and Park Overall's LaVerne in NBC's
"Empty Nest.";    When this sitcom began three seasons ago, most of the
attention went to star Richard Mulligan and the actresses cast as his two
daughters, Kristy McNichol and Dinah Manoff. But Leisure, the former "Joe
Izuzu" of TV commercials, and newcomer Overall quickly elbowed their way into
the front row with fans. Leisure's sleazy Charley, the neighbor who spends
more time in your refrigerator than his own, and Overall's quick-witted,
Southern-fried nurse LaVerne are people "Empty Nest" can't do without.;   
(box) Laurie Metcalf's Jackie Harris in ABC's "Roseanne.";    Metcalf's
Jackie, unmarried sister to Roseanne Conner (Roseanne Barr), is a rare sitcom
creation: A well-rounded character who's shown us her wretched, forlorn side
as often as her fractiously funny side. Metcalf's crisp comedy timing and her
skill at conveying Jackie's vulnerability help give this show the bite that
lifts it above the ordinary.;    (box) Beverly Archer's Alva "Gunny" Bricker
on CBS's "Major Dad.";    Archer's deadpan delivery and de-sexed military look
as Gunnery Sgt. Bricker help make her the best anti-femme TV character since
Nancy Kulp's classic Jane Hathaway in "The Beverly Hillbillies." Funny thing
is, "Gunny" turns into a bunny when she's out on a date, and the talented
Archer revels in throwing us that occasional change-up.  </TEXT>
