<HEADLINE>  DIRECTOR'S CHAIR IS UNEMPLOYMENT HEDGE FOR
STARS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Television  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   HARDLY anyone looks at the director's credit on a TV sitcom, but one name
might catch your eye as it zips by in the opening moments of tonight's episode
of CBS's "The Family Man": Mark-Linn Baker.;    That's right, it's the same
Mark-Linn Baker who plays dippy Larry on ABC's "Perfect Strangers." You
wouldn't expect him to be able to direct you to the men's room, right?;    So
maybe you happened to spot the director's credit in last week's episode of the
same sitcom: Scott Baio.;    That's no mistake either. He's the same Scott
Baio who used to go by the name Chachi on "Happy Days" and its spinoff,
"Joannie Loves Chachi." He seems marginally better suited to the job of
director. After all, wasn't his last TV series called "Charles in Charge"?;   
What's going on here?;    Actually, nothing that unusual. Off-camera, Baker is
much more ambitious and intelligent than the character he plays, while Baio is
much more serious and sophisticated than you'd believe from his boyish TV
roles. Both are veterans of years in sitcoms, guys who know the score when it
comes to TV comedy.;    That's why they're wisely developing their
behind-the-camera skills, perhaps preparing for that day when acting jobs may
be harder to come by and no longer creative enough to satisfy them.;    Though
Baker is still the star of a hit series and Baio remains in demand as an
actor, they're both following a well-worn trail in television that frequently
leads to even more success for sitcom stars.;    Here are some examples of
other TV sitcom stars who branched out into directing and did even better:;   
(check) The late Jerry Paris, best known as Rob Petrie's next-door neighbor,
Jerry Helper, on "The Dick Van Dyke Show," turned director in the late 1960s
and rarely acted again. He was the regular director of one of TV's
longest-running hits, "Happy Days," and did a number of feature films,
including "The Grasshopper" with Jacqueline Bisset, "Never A Dull Moment" with
Van Dyke, and the second and third "Police Academy" sequels, both huge hits.; 
  (check) Rob Reiner, the former Mike "Meathead" Stivic of "All in the
Family," first dabbled in TV directing, then switched to features in the 1980s
with a series of hits from "This is Spinal Tap" and "Stand by Me" to "The
Princess Bride," "When Harry Met Sally" and last year's "Misery.";    (check)
Penny Marshall, Reiner's ex-wife, left the role of Laverne DeFazio on "Laverne
&amp; Shirley" to try directing. After a couple of false starts, she hit it big
with "Big" and last year's "Awakenings" for the big screen.;    (check) Ron
Howard, one of several "Happy Days" alumni who turned to directing, learned
his craft by keeping his eyes open during his many years as a juvenile actor
and breaking into features with the 1977 exploitation film "Grand Theft Auto."
Now he's one of Hollywood's most important directors after hits like
"Splash!," "Cocoon," "Gung Ho," "Parenthood" and the current "Backdraft.";   
(check) Bill Bixby, the former star of "The Courtship of Eddie's Father"
sitcom, began shifting to directing in the 1970s with a series of TV pilot
episodes and made-for-TV features like "The Barbary Coast" and "Three On a
Date." He even directed himself in the last two "Incredible Hulk" movies.;   
(check) Alan Alda, star of the long-running "M(*)A(*)S(*)H" series, directed
many episodes of his own series and successfully switched to feature films in
the 1980s with "The Four Seasons," "Sweet Liberty" and, most recently,
"Betsy's Wedding.";    (check) Richard Benjamin, the star of TV's "He and She"
series, edged into directing in the 1970s and scored a big hit with his first
feature film, 1982's "My Favorite Year" (which starred Mark-Linn Baker). Now
primarily a director, he has done such films as "City Heat" with Clint
Eastwood and Burt Reynolds and "The Money Pit" with Tom Hanks and Shelley
Long.;    (check) Jackie Cooper, the former movie child star, became a TV
comedy star with his 1959-62 CBS sitcom "Hennesey" but soon earned a
reputation as one of the best directors of comedy pilots. Though he still
acts, Cooper is mainly a director of TV movies such as "Rosie: The Rosemary
Clooney Story" and "Rainbow.";    (check) Danny DeVito, though still a top
comedy star, has established glowing credits as a director since he made his
first TV movie, "The Ratings Game," for cable's Movie Channel in 1984. Among
his hits: "Throw Momma From the Train" (1987), "War of the Roses" (1989).;   
Making good on that first directing break isn't easy, but heads-up actors such
as Baker and Baio know it's worth the effort, because there's no predicting
how long their starring days will last.;    Maybe that's why Michael J. Fox,
"Family Ties" sitcom star turned movie star ("Back to the Future I, II &amp;
III"), just broke into directing with an episode of HBO's "Tales from the
Crypt." You never can tell when that credit may come in handy.  </TEXT>
