<HEAD>NBC and ABC Unveil Fall Lines; `Twin Peaks' Renewed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-ABC-NBC Lineup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Twin Peaks'' returns to ABC's fall schedule
despite slipping ratings in a ``bold experiment'' to lure viewers
back to the tube on Saturday nights, the network's entertainment
chief says.
   ``When you think about it, the idea grows on you,'' Robert A.
Eiger told a gathering of network advertisers Monday.
   ``One, there are a lot of young adult viewers home on Saturday
night with nothing to watch so they go out and rent videotapes. And
two, we think this show can prosper when we move it away from that
real tough `Cheers' competition on Thursday night.''
   NBC, revealing its fall schedule later in the day, went for the
laugh track with six situation comedies among nine new shows. That
makes 17 sitcoms on NBC next fall, its most ever.
   ABC opens its Saturday night gamble with the Western ``Young
Riders,'' followed by the critically praised Vietnam series ``China
Beach'' and then ``Twin Peaks,'' the moody drama created by film
director David Lynch.
   ``We're going for the gold with three special programs in an
all-out attempt to change the perception of Saturday night
television,'' Eiger said.
   ``Twin Peaks'' will debut with a two-hour movie and will take
less of a serial approach, more akin to ``Hill Street Blues,'' he
said.
   NBC's hourlong series are ``Signs of Life,'' a
patient's-eye-view ``reality'' program about medicine; ``Law and
Order,'' about criminal justice from arrest through trial, and the
musical comedy ``Hull Street High.''
   The network, which just won the prime time ratings for the fifth
consecutive season, renewed ``Grand,'' ``Wings'' and ``Carol &amp;
Co,'' but axed 4-season-old ``ALF,'' ``227,'' ``Baywatch,'' ``My
Two Dads'' and `Mancuso FBI.''
   Two of NBC's new sitcoms are based on movies, ``Parenthood'' and
``Ferris Bueller.'' The others are rap-driven ``Fresh Prince of Bel
Air,'' ``The Fanelli Boys'' and ``Working It Out,'' which co-stars
Jane Curtin, formerly of CBS' ``Kate &amp; Allie,'' playing a divorced
person.
   ABC, with six new shows, also offers a musical hour in Steven
Bochco's ``Cop Rock,'' an intriguing combination of police action
and Randy Newman's music reminiscent of the PBS hit ``The Singing
Detective.''
   ABC dropped six low-rated series: ``Elvis,'' tales of the King
when he was a youth, ``Brewster Place,'' with Oprah Winfrey,
``Capital News,'' ``The Marshall Chronicles,'' `H.E.L.P.'' and
``Sunset Beat.''
   CBS' schedule may come out later this week or early next week, a
spokesman said. Fox Broadcasting said it will release its lineup
May 29.
   ``Twin Peaks,'' a tangled saga of sex, lies and death in the
Northwest, was this season's most talked-about series. It started
strong on April 8, winning with a 21.7 rating, but has lost more
than 50 percent of its viewers.
   Its season finale Wednesday should have high ratings because it
resolves the murder of high school beauty queen Laura Palmer, a
mystery that prompted ``I Killed Laura Palmer'' T-shirts in
California.
   Last Thursday's show gave the series its lowest Nielsens to date
_ a 10.6 rating and a 17 percent audience share. Each ratings point
represents 921,000 homes.
   Other ABC renewals include the high-rated ``Roseanne'' and
``thirtysomething,'' ``Life Goes On'' and ABC News' ``PrimeTime
Live'' and ``20-20.''
   Three of the new series on ABC's roster are sitcoms _ ``Baby
Talk,'' based on the hit movie ``Look Who's Talking''; ``Going
Places,'' about four young adults in Los Angeles working on their
first TV show _ a ``candid videos'' series; and ``Married People,''
about three generations of couples sharing a brownstone in New York.
   Capitalizing on its top-rated ``America's Funniest Home
Videos,'' ABC also will have ``America's Funniest ... Part II.''
   James Earl Jones, whose ``Paris'' police series on CBS flopped a
decade ago, will try again in a new hourlong ABC series,
``Gabriel's Fire,'' playing an ex-convict working as a private
investigator for a defense attorney.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

