<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
TV: Rock, Dance and Pre-Halloween Thrillers
---
By Martha Bayles</HL>
<DD> 10/15/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<TEXT>
   Saturday, Oct. 17, 8 p.m.-conclusion EDT, on ABC: The first game of the 1987 World Series. 
This year's Series may not be as exciting as last year's, but it will probably beat the football season! 

   Weekly, beginning Oct. 19, various times, on PBS (check local listings; Wednesday, Oct. 21, 6-6:30 p.m. EDT, on WNET): "Rockschool." 
Don't worry if your kids get hooked on this 24-part series about rock music. 
Hosted by Herbie Hancock, it will teach them something about music theory, craft and technique -- to say nothing of high-tech instrumentation. 
It's so interesting, you might get hooked, too. 

   Monday, Oct. 19, 9-11 p.m. EDT, on NBC: "Strange Voices." 
One of the facts of life not dealt with on the sitcom "Facts of Life" is schizophrenia. 
In this TV movie, a regular on that sitcom, Nancy McKeon, plays a mentally ill college student. 

   Wednesday, Oct. 21, various times, on PBS (PBS dates and times vary, so check local listings): The year's first "Mark Russell Comedy Special." 
The Washington-based political satirist says, "This is my busy season . . . if I owned a department store, it would be five days before Christmas." 

   Wednesday, Oct. 21, 10-11 p.m. EDT, on PBS: "Legacy of the Hollywood Blacklist." 
What do we learn from this film? 
That late-1940s anti-communism was just "paranoia"; that the Hollywood 10 were just "progressives"; and that PBS favors the manipulative ideologues of the left over those of the right. 

   Thursday, Oct. 22, 9-10 p.m. EDT, on A&amp;E (repeated at 1 a.m. and on Oct 25): "Baryshnikov: The Dancer and the Dance." 
This British-made documentary takes an intimate look at ballet's monarch. 

   Friday, Oct. 23, 8-10 p.m. EDT, on A&amp;E (repeated at midnight and on Oct. 24); "After Pilkington." 
This dark, subtle film is too psychological for a murder mystery, too intricately plotted for a love story. 
British playwright Simon Gray has a gift for making us care for unlovable people. 

   Friday, Oct. 23, 9-10 p.m. EDT, on PBS: "David Gordon's Made in U.S.A." 
If you crave more Baryshnikov, tune in for this innovative "Great Performances" premiere, featuring avant-garde choreography by Mr. Gordon, direction by Don Mischer (who staged the Emmy-winning Tony Awards), and graphics by video artists John Sanborn and Mary Perillo. 

   Saturday, Oct. 24, 10-11 p.m. EDT, on HBO (repeated Oct. 27, 30 and Nov. dates TBA): "HBO World Stage: Billy Joel From Leningrad, USSR." 
That's right, folks -- Leningrad, back in the U.S.S.R., not Leningrad, Maine. 
Don't miss the first no-holds-barred American rock concert in the Soviet Union, made possible by the General Exchanges Agreement signed at the 1985 Geneva summit. 
Joel's much-publicized public tantrum not included. 

   Sunday, Oct. 25, 3:30-6 p.m. EST, on ABC: "The McDonald's Basketball Open." 
More dizzying cultural exchange. 
Having already played Tracer Milan, the Italian team that currently holds the European championship, the Milwaukee Bucks will go on to represent the NBA against the Soviet National Team. 

   Sunday, Oct. 25, 9-11 p.m. EST, on NBC: "Bay Coven." 
Avoid quiet New England villages! 
According to this movie with Pamela Sue Martin (formerly of "Dynasty"), the witch hunters of the 17th century didn't finish the job. 

   Monday, Oct. 26, 9-11 p.m. EST, on NBC: "Deep Dark Secrets." 
Avoid country inns! 
This second pre-Halloween hair-raiser is about the young co-manager of such an establishment, who discovers the shocking truth about her partner/hubby. 
Out-in-the-sticks thrillers must attract "Dynasty" graduates; this one stars Pamela Bellwood. 

</TEXT>
</DOC>

