<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Television:
   Old Faces and Concepts Return to Tube
   ----
   By Robert Goldberg
</HL>
<DATE>
09/16/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<LP>
   Once a year, every year, TV's premiere week rolls around.
I think of it like the holiday season. There are all sorts of
new programs, like gift-wrapped boxes sitting under the tree,
and every one is a chance for something really good. Well,
this week a new TV season begins, but all you'll find in
these boxes are hand-me-downs -- beatup sweaters and
out-of-date ties.
   The stars of the 1991-92 season are the old standbys --
James Garner, Carol Burnett, Redd Foxx -- and the concepts
are just as faded: cops, lawyers, and families with living
rooms. In fact, everyone's moving back into the living room
this year. A divorced daughter and her kids move back on "The
Royal Family" (CBS, Wednesday, 8 p.m. EDT), a long-lost
brother on "Flesh 'n' Blood" (NBC, Friday, 9:30 p.m.), a
sister on "Sibs" (ABC, Wednesday, 9:30 p.m.), returning GIs
on "Homefront" (ABC, Tuesday, 10 p.m., starting Sept. 24).
</LP>
<TEXT>
   This all makes sense, because you might say that the
networks themselves are moving back into the living room.
Last year, like intrepid teens, they went out into the wide
world of experimentation. They played around with offbeat
concepts like "Twin Peaks" and "Cop Rock," and by their
standards, they failed miserably: There were no hits last
season, and advertising revenues have been dropping. Small
wonder the networks have decided to come back to the cozy
security of the living room -- the known and safe haven of
sitcomland -- to curl up on the family sofa.
   The show that epitomizes this backward-think is "Step by
Step" (ABC, Friday, 8:30 p.m.). The stars, Patrick Duffy and
Suzanne Somers, are recycled from "Dallas" and "Three's
Company," respectively. Then there's the concept. It's the
story of a single mother with three children. And it's the
story, of a man named Duffy, who was busy raising three kids
of his own. They were four kids, living all together, yet
they were all alone. Till the one day when the lady met this
fellow, and they knew that it was much more than a hunch.
That this group would somehow form a family, and that's the
way they all became the Brady Bunch. The Brady Bunch . . .
oops.
   With its two parents and its six kids, "Step by Step" may
seem exactly like "The Brady Bunch," but actually, there's a
1990s twist: The two sets of kids don't really like each
other] Well, maybe that was in "The Brady Bunch" too. I can't
remember. But this one definitely doesn't have a housekeeper
named Alice.
   Instead, it's got food fights and jokes about zits and
cute kids making snide remarks. Plus it's got lines like, "I
know I'm not your mother, but I would really like to be your
friend."
   And it has sex.
   In fact, this whole season seems to be oozing sexuality.
People are pawing at one another, rubbing up against each
other, taking off their clothes at the slightest provocation.
From "Step by Step" to "Roc" (Fox, Sunday, 8:30 p.m.) to
"Home Improvement" (ABC, Tuesday, 8:30 p.m.), everyone's
talking trash and getting primed to hop into the sack. The
middle-aged folks are going for it on "Sibs." The old folks
are going for it on "The Royal Family." I can't tell if this
is a good sign or a bad sign, but it's definitely a trend.
   And speaking of trends, the most interesting one this
season is how many shows are striving to be politically
correct. Call it the PC season. Blacks, women, the poor, even
the deaf -- they all get to speak out against oppression. On
"Homefront," women get booted out of jobs by returning male
GIs; on "Teach" (CBS, Wednesday, 8:30 p.m.), a black music
teacher in an all-white prep school is told he wouldn't even
have his job if they didn't need a token; on the sitcom "The
Torkelsons" (NBC, Friday, 10 p.m.), a dirt-poor Okie family
must struggle to hold off the reposessors; and "Reasonable
Doubts" (NBC, Friday, 10 p.m.), stars hearing-impaired
actress Marlee Maitlin. At least the networks are trying. But
unfortunately, all they've been able to prove so far is that
they're able to make minorities look just as foolish as
everyone else.
   There is one exception, a show that's more than just PC.
It's a one-hour drama called "I'll Fly Away" (NBC, Tuesday, 8
p.m., starting Oct. 8), and I think it will be one of the
very best of the new season. Set against the volatile decade
when the civil rights movement was just beginning, it's the
tale of a Southern district attorney (Sam Waterston) raising
his three kids with the help of a black housekeeper (Regina
Taylor).
   Of course, "I'll Fly Away" owes a clear debt to "To Kill a
Mockingbird," but whatever the inspiration, it offers a
special sensitivity in both its writing and its acting, a
subtlety rarely seen on weekly TV. In a world of black and
white, no one is painted black or white. Catch it fast,
because this excellent program is just the kind of show that
might get canceled very soon.
   In almost every way, "I'll Fly Away" is swimming against
the tide. It's a one-hour drama trying to survive in a season
of half-hour sitcoms, a season with laugh tracks all around
the dial. In fact, posterity may well record 1991-92 as the
great reflowering of the sitcom. Rarely have there been so
many, and rarely have they been done better. The form's great
practitioners (James L. Brooks, James Burrows, Susan Harris,
Gary David Goldberg, Stan Daniels) have returned, and notable
actors like David Keith, Marsha Mason and the Broadway cast
of "Piano Lesson" have been enlisted.
   This means that the networks will be all the more shocked
when these terminally silly programs do nothing to halt the
steady erosion of viewers. When their best shot -- the old
tried and true -- doesn't work, things should get pretty
interesting around the networks. There'll be some real drama.
   In the meantime, this season does offer a couple of
programs that look to the future instead of the past,
programs with a little inventiveness: "Herman's Head" (Fox,
Sunday, 9:30 p.m.) and "Eerie, Indiana" (NBC, Sunday, 7:30
p.m.). You won't mistake either for high art, but both have a
sense of fun and imagination. And both will be written about
in future columns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

