<HEAD>Helmond: Role on Hit Show an `Afterthought'</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Katherine Helmond's juicy role as the hip
mother with the swinging lifestyle was an afterthought when the hit
ABC comedy ``Who's the Boss?'' was being created, the actress said.
   ``The show was originally written for two sisters, one a working
woman and one with lots of children,'' said Helmond. ``One was a
go-getter, the other was very domestic.
   ``But they found that combination never clicked. They read a lot
of young ladies. But they felt it turned out to be kind of sour
grapes. Each sister seemed a little envious of the other. No matter
how many times they rehearsed it, they couldn't make it funny.''
   It finally occurred to the producers to give Judith Light a
mother as a sparring partner. Tony Danza stars as an ex-boxer who
becomes a housekeeper.
   ``When my name came up at a casting session I was doing a play
in San Francisco,'' said Helmond, who plays Mona Robinson. ``I
asked them, `What are you looking for?' They said a mother who
causes trouble, but in a funny way. I said she'd have to be someone
underfoot all the time. I got ideas from my grandmother who lived
with us. She was very funny, very even-handed and right in the
middle of everything. A big, strapping Irish woman with red hair,
one of those Texas women who says whatever she thinks.''
   The pilot for ``Who's the Boss?'' created a triangle of three
totally different people.
   ``But somehow, that triangle works,'' she said. ``This man who
takes care of the house, a highly successful woman who can't do a
thing at home and her mother. I think a lot of families today are
made up of different elements. Two divorced women living together,
two fathers. I think the cost of living today has contributed to
these kind of made-up families.''
   Helmond grew up in Galveston, Texas, and got her early dramatic
training in Houston and Dallas. She moved on to New York, where she
was nominated for a Tony for her performance in Eugene O'Neill's
``The Great God Brown'' in 1973. She was in numerous other
productions, but she's best known for her role as Jessica Tate in
the satirical comedy series ``Soap.''
   Her latest movie is ``Shadey,'' made in England, but she's also
been in ``Time Bandits,'' ``Brazil,'' ``Overboard,'' ``Family
Plot,'' ``The Hindenburg'' and ``The Baby Blue Marine.''
   She is married to sculptor David Christian, but lately he has
also taken up writing. He recently adapted a short story by
Somerset Maugham for a TV film to be called ``Plain Jane.''
   ``He had to update it,'' she said. ``We didn't realize how
difficult it would be to get the rights. It took 18 months because
there are so many heirs. And the British don't move very fast.
   ``I'll play Jane. I think we may do it in Texas because we'd get
some help there. Jane's a woman who goes through a total
metamorphosis. She changes as does the world around her. She
becomes a woman who can live in the world.''
   Her husband started writing when she enrolled in the women's
directing program at the American Film Institute. She needed a
project immediately, so he adapted a Raymond Carver short story.
Her film ``Bankrupt'' is one of six films from the course that was
selected to be shown on the Arts &amp; Entertainment Channel.
   She and Christian own homes in Los Angeles and Long Island and
have apartments in New York and London.
   ``We've just gone through remodeling our home here,'' she said.
``It was a 1932 house, and all the wiring and plumbing had to be
redone. The city building inspector gave it approval the other day.
It took two years. We're giving a big party for all the workers and
our neighbors, who also had to put up with all the inconvenience.
   ``Our London apartment is in an old neighborhood near Baker
Street. I love going to the fishmonger, the greengrocer, the
bakery. You have to bring your own plastic bags. The first time,
they asked me if I had any plastic. I thought they meant a credit
card.''
</TEXT>
