<TEXT>     Think about it:;   Bob Saget and Dave Coulier have ABC's "Full House," and
other ABC shows they host separately -- Saget's "America's Funniest Home
Videos" and Coulier's "America's Funniest People.";   Roseanne Barr has ABC's
"Roseanne." Jerry Seinfeld has "Seinfeld," Woody Harrelson has "Cheers" and
Marsha Warfield has "Night Court," all on NBC. Pam Stone is a regular on ABC's
"Coach," which stars Craig T. Nelson, who started out as a stand-up.;   And
there is, of course, TV's current granddaddy of stand-up, Bill Cosby of NBC's
"The Cosby Show.";   Although stand-up comics have been finding homes in
sitcoms since TV began, a deluge is now in progress. Any stand-up with any
kind of following now seems to be getting an invitation to join a sitcom.;  
Next month, for example, Tim Allen brings his handyman/philosopher persona to
ABC as the star of "Home Improvement" on Tuesday nights at 8:30.;   Also
arriving this season are wacky Jeff Altman and smoky-voiced Stephanie Hodge in
NBC's "Nurses" on Saturday nights at 9.;    Meanwhile, back at the raunch; Due
later in the season is raunchy Sam Kinison, whose "Charlie Hoover" is a backup
show for the Fox schedule.;   Still on hand is San Jose's Kevin Pollak, whose
"Morton &amp; Hayes" is finishing a CBS summer run on Wednesday nights at 8:30.;  
And returning this fall after a long absence from prime time is the legendary
Dirty Old Man of stand-up, Redd Foxx, who will star in CBS's "The Royal
Family" on Wednesday nights at 8.;   There's a good reason for the stand-up
stampede: Most of these comics already have a following among the young adults
network advertisers most want to reach.;   Another reason: Most situation
comedies are filmed or taped in front of a live audience, and many producers
of comedy shows feel stand-up comics fit perfectly into such an environment.; 
 "They have all this experience working in front of audiences, like the old
vaudevillians," said producer-director Rob Reiner, whose company produces
"Morton &amp; Hayes" and "Seinfeld.";   Reiner worked as a sitcom actor for years
-- he was Mike "Meathead" Stivic in the classic "All in the Family" -- and
knows an experienced stand-up has an edge over a movie-trained actor when
breaking into the sitcom field.;   "They've learned what's funny by playing in
front of a live crowd," he said. "That's the best training ground you can
have.";   Still, it's not automatically easy for every stand-up to break into
acting with an ensemble of other performers, speaking lines written by someone
else, especially if they're used to standing out there alone, performing their
own material.;   "It's a bit of a problem," says Seinfeld, who usually writes
his own material from personal experiences but now has three other writers
turning out lines for his sitcom character. "I always have to change them into
my rhythm to feel comfortable.";   In contrast, Lewis, whose show will be on
opposite Seinfeld's this fall, has adjusted to delivering other people's lines
and now enjoys the relief from his stand-up work.;   "It's certainly nice to
be on stage with some people," he said. "When you do stand-up, which is pretty
courageous for anybody, you live and die by your own jokes.";   Stop me if
you've heard this; Coulier of "Full House" says a major adjustment was
learning how to play to the same live crowd with the same jokes for all the
retakes sitcom work requires. Newcomer Allen is now trying to learn the same
lesson.;   "What's odd is to do it several times to the same crowd," said
Allen.;   It was unnerving, he said, to do your line, get a big laugh from the
studio audience, then learn you'd have to do it again because the lighting
wasn't right.;   "I can't do it again. These people just saw this," Allen
protested at first. Now he's trying to accept doing gags over and over for
fewer laughs, although he admits, "That's taken some time getting used to.";  
For Lewis, there was some trouble learning how to apply the technique he'd
learned over a decade of stand-up comedy in an environment where you have to
hit your marks for the cameras and wait for line cues.;   "As a stand-up, I'm
basically myself -- unfortunately," he said. "But when you do a show as an
actor, you have to listen. You're part of an ensemble.";   Some TV producers
believe stand-ups become, by necessity, good actors in order to work
successfully in front of crowds, so the transition to working with others
shouldn't be hard for them.;   Fed up with stand-up; "We didn't go out looking
for stand-up comics," explained writer-producer Susan Harris, who gave Billy
Crystal his first big TV break with a role on her "Soap" and now has cast two
stand-ups, Altman and Hodge, in her "Nurses.";   Instead, said Harris, she
pays attention to basic acting skills, not the venue in which her cast members
have been demonstrating those skills most recently.;   That's fine with Hodge,
who, like many stand-ups, was trained first as an actor and only took up
stand-up comedy to "gain maturity, life experience and a little more courage
and a lot more confidence than I had at the time.";   Hodge, in fact, hopes
"Nurses" clicks, so she can leave stand-up behind.;   "It's a bizarre
lifestyle," she said, "because you're extraordinarily creative for small
spurts of time, and the rest of the time you feel like this sort of lump,
alone in a bad hotel where no one really cares.";   Lewis shares Hodge's
desire to move away from stand-up, but for different reasons. After rising to
the top of the stand-up heap -- he once played Carnegie Hall to a sellout
crowd -- he's not sure it can satisfy him creatively much longer.;   "I've
done it," said Lewis. "I don't mean to sound like a prima donna, but I have 10
or 12 cassettes on the market. I've done 50 Lettermans. After you play
Carnegie Hall, there's a point where you say you're not going back to those
clubs and work out every night. I don't need to. Now I'm more interested in
acting and writing movie scripts.";   Though Lewis is in a successful show and
has begun to get big roles in feature films, he's still not the kind of
overnight ratings sensation Barr was for ABC. Few stand-ups are so lucky. And
they certainly don't come with money-back guarantees.;   And boy, are my jokes
tired; Among the more recent failures: CBS's 1990-91 flop "Lenny," starring
blue-collar comic Lenny Clarke, and Jackie Mason in ABC's "Chicken Soup" the
year before.;   Yet TV history is loaded with stand-up stars who were
enormously successful in sitcoms -- such as Crystal, Don Adams, George Gobel,
Freddie Prinze, Jimmie Walker, Gabe Kaplan, Robin Williams -- and even a few
who became TV legends, such as Red Skelton, Danny Thomas and Bob Newhart.;  
"There are a great many stand-up comedians they've tried to write sitcoms for
and failed," says TV producer Greg Antonacci, who's doing Foxx's new show.
"What's important is that the persona fit the character.";   Seinfeld agrees
"absolutely." His NBC series is so closely patterned after his own life that
it even includes his club stand-up routines each week. The only difference
between the TV Jerry and the real Jerry, says Seinfeld, "is that he doesn't
have a sitcom yet.";   Seinfeld says he's a student of his craft and knew it
would be a great mistake for him to play a different kind of character in a
sitcom.;   "It took me 15 years to figure out what people think is funny about
me," he said.;   Most of the younger stand-ups now working in sitcoms also
believe it's fatal to veer too far from their stand-up persona. Coulier, for
example, is able to use the "funny noises" that made him a stand-up smash to
amuse the youngsters he works with in "Full House." ABC has built Allen's
"Home Improvement" around his "men are pigs" routine as a pro-male handyman
version of Robert Bly. Hodge's "Nurses" character is just as "angry" as her
stand-up character.;   Standing in sharp contrast, though, is Foxx, whose
legendary stand-up status came from blue material he couldn't use in his big
NBC hit, "Sanford and Son." Today, Foxx's stand-up material seems soapy clean
in contrast to what the youngsters are doing.;   "Every comedian on Earth is
dirtier than me now," he said.;   If a stand-up star also becomes a sitcom
star, the TV series almost always broadens the appeal of the comic whenever he
or she does the stand-up act again. Coulier and Seinfeld, for instance, now
play to huge crowds after years in front of modest ones.;   But for some,
sitcom success means an end to stand-up work and a transition into full-time
acting in TV or movies. Altman of "Nurses" says that won't happen to him, no
matter how well the show does.;   "It's something you do because you're nuts,
and you have to find some sort of venue that will take you," he said. "The
stage of stand-up comedy is that place. If I never did another club again, I
would still go up to the Comedy Store or the Improv and get up on stage,
because I can't not do it."  </TEXT>
