<HEAD>`Major League' Still In First Place</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 17th graf, `7.``Cyborg'' ...' to CORRECT number of weeks
in release to two sted one.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Major League,'' a baseball spoof based on the
losing reputation of the Cleveland Indians, earned more than $7
million last weekend to remain in first place in box office revenue.
   Next was ``The Dream Team,'' which earned $4.3 million for its
second week of release.
   In third and fourth place were ``Say Anything'' and ``She's Out
Of Control,'' _ both about youngwomen, their suitors, and concerned
fathers. Both also star the daughters of former pop stars.
   ``Say Anything,'' starring John Cusack and Ione Skye, daughter
of 1960s folk-rock singer Donovan, earned $4 million in its debut.
Cusack's character pursues the younger woman played by Skye.
   ``She's Out Of Control,'' starring Tony Danza and Ami Dolenz,
daughter of Monkees pop group member Mickey Dolenz, earned $3.6
million. Danza plays a single father who's overwhelmed by his
daughter's maturing ito a woman.
   In fifth place was quadruple-Oscar winner ``Rain Man,'' which
sold $3 million in tickets.
   ``Disorganized Crime,'' another debut movie, earned $2.8 million
for sixth place. The movie starring former Munster Fred Gwynne and
salsa musician Ruben Blades is about a group of bandits planning a
heist while being chased by a couple of cops from New Jersey.
   The future action-drama ``Cyborg'' earned $1.84 million for
seventh place, while the ocean thriller ``Dead Calm'' was in eighth
with $1.80 million.
   In ninth place was ``Fletch Lives'' with $1.5 million. ``The
Rescuers'' was 10th with just over $1 million.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``Major League,'' Paramount, $7 million, 1,615 screens,
$4,378 per screen, $18.4 million, two weeks.
   2. ``The Dream Team,'' Universal, $4.3 million, 1,354 screens,
$3,180 per screen, $11.5 million, two weeks.
   3. ``Say Anything,'' 20th Century Fox, $4 million, 1,113
screens, $3,646 per screen, $4,058,496, one week.
   4. ``She's Out Of Control,'' Weintraub Entertainment, $3.6
million, 987 screens, $3,701 per screen, $3,653,142, one week.
   5. ``Rain Man,'' MGM-UA, $3 million, 1,580 screens, $1,981 per
screen, $152.3 million, 18 weeks.
   6. ``Disorganized Crime,'' Walt Disney, $2.8 million 1,462
screens, $1,943 per screen, $2,840,166, one week.
   7. ``Cyborg,'' Cannon, $1.84 million, 830 screens, $2,220 per
screen, $5.9 million, two weeks.
   8. ``Dead Calm,'' Warner Bros., $1.80 million, 959 screens,
$1,884 per screen, $5.1 million, two weeks.
   9. ``Fletch Lives,'' Universal, $1.5 million, 1,346 screens,
$1,185 per screen, $29.4 million, five weeks.
   10. ``The Rescuers,'' Walt Disney, $1 million, 1,366 screens,
$777 per screen, $17.6 million, five weeks.
